Russian President Vladimir Putin signed the law on the introduction of administrative liability for violation of the term and procedure of payment of goods (works, services) when carrying out procurement for state and municipal needs.
This law is intended to solve the very acute problem of non-fulfillment of their obligations by customers in the implementation of state and municipal procurement.
Two years ago, the situation where entrepreneurs could not get paid for already executed state and municipal contracts was ubiquitous.
At the same time, the President of Russia instructed the Prosecutor General of the Russian Federation to take the problem under special control.
Because businessmen themselves could not cope with unfair customers, who concluded contracts not supported by funding, tried in every way to evade the commitments to pay and included illegal terms in contracts.
The problem is systemic throughout the country.
Since 2015, in the interests of protecting the rights of entrepreneurs to receive payment for public orders, the Prosecutor’s Office has submitted 9,7 thousand submissions, according to the results of their consideration, 4,5 thousand officials have been brought to disciplinary responsibility, to administrative - 533, 75 materials have been submitted to the investigative bodies for the organization of procedural checks, 46 of them have been opened criminal cases.
As a result, the debt to entrepreneurs in the amount of more than 66 billion rubles was paid.
Moreover, these huge sums were accumulated far from the non-payment of multi-billion-dollar contracts.
The famous debts resulted in numerous, systematic delays in the payment of services to entrepreneurs for much more modest amounts.
This is a characteristic case.
The head of a small company won a competition for the provision of services on social transportation for several million rubles.
The man invested all his working funds, fully fulfilled his obligations, but did not receive the money in time.
The result is a growing financial volume of debt on wages, taxes, loans, which would have led to bankruptcy if the entrepreneur did not seek help from the prosecutor’s office.
In some regions, the problem has been minimized.
Nevertheless, as of the first half of 2017, the total amount of debt under state and municipal contracts identified by prosecutors of the constituent entities of the Russian Federation amounted to about 27.4 billion rubles.
In regions where indebtedness continues to reach critical values, the prosecutor’s office operates in the mode of manual anti-crisis management.
The Prosecutor General personally holds exit meetings with representatives of the local authorities, at which all violations discovered by prosecutors and measures for their immediate elimination are subjectly examined.
Such operational meetings this year have already been held in Yaroslavl and Yekaterinburg.
Federal Law No. 189-FZ "On Amendments to the Code of the Russian Federation on Administrative Offences as regards the establishment of administrative responsibility of officials of the customer for violation of the deadline and procedure for payment of goods (works, services) during procurement for state and municipal needs"
The draft law was developed by the Ministry of Economic Development of Russia at the initiative of the Prosecutor General’s Office.
The new law will supplement the Code of the Russian Federation on administrative offences with an article that provides for a fine from 30 thousand to 50 thousand rubles for violation by an official of the customer of the term and procedure for payment of goods, works and services in state and municipal procurement.
If the official has already been subjected to administrative punishment for a similar offence, he is disqualified for a period of one to two years.
All prosecutors of the constituent entities of the Russian Federation have already been instructed to ensure the application of these legislative novels in practice.
Civil Rights Group Announces Warning on Movement in Missouri
The National Association for the Advancement of Color Population has issued a warning for colored people traveling to Missouri because of the state’s discriminatory policies and racist attacks.
The group’s statement reads as follows: “The National Association for the Advancement of Colour People’s Travel Warning, valid until August 28, 2017, calls on African-American travelers, guests and citizens of Missouri to be careful and to exercise extra caution when traveling across the state in connection with a series of suspicious racist incidents that have recently occurred across the state and have been cited here.”
According to the National Association for the Advancement of Coloured People, a recent Missouri law has made it harder for people to win lawsuits related to discrimination and the fact that state law enforcement agencies disproportionately often choose minority persons as their objects.
“People are being violated human rights.
They are stopped on the roads because of their skin colour, beaten and killed,” said Rod Chapel, president of the National Association for the Advancement of Colored People in Missouri.
“We hear complaints more often than ever before.”
This is the first warning of its kind issued by the organization to the U.S. state.
The group cited incidents such as the racial humiliation of black students at the University of Missouri and the death of twenty-eight-year-old Tory Sanders, a black man from Tennessee.
Sanders was killed in suspicious circumstances earlier this year after he had run out of gasoline while traveling through the state, and the Missouri police arrested him without being charged with the crime.
The warning also mentions a recent report by the Missouri General Prosecutor’s Office that black drivers are 75 percent more likely to be stopped on the road than white drivers.
“The purpose of the warning is for people to be aware of the situation and to warn their relatives and friends and colleagues about what could happen in Missouri,” Chapel said.
“People need to be prepared in one way or another whether they will take money with them for collateral or tell relatives that they are traveling across the state.”
According to the latest data from the FBI reporting program on hate crimes, Missouri recorded 100 hate crimes in 2015, making the state 16th in the state for such violations.
The move warning is also a response to a new Missouri law, after which it will be more difficult to bring a lawsuit against a legal entity for housing or labor discrimination.
Earlier, the American Civil Liberties Union (ACLU) issued warnings for travelers across Texas and Arizona after these states passed new immigration control laws that ordered local law enforcement agencies to arrest people for violating immigration laws, which ACLU believes should have increased the number of racial checks.
Movement warnings are typically issued by the State Department for other countries, but recently public organizations have resorted to this measure in response to certain laws and trends within the United States.
