The citizens are not relaxed.
Compliance with the basic rules is strictly monitored.
Let’s say, if a minor is sold cigarettes in a kiosk, then everyone in the chain will be punished: the store owner will pay a huge amount, the offender himself will be hit with sticks on the “back”, and the seller will also be ripped out and imprisoned.
It is because of such strict laws that crimes are very rare in Singapore.
Is this justified?
In the 1970s, there was chaos on the roads - motorists ignored the lighting, drove as they wanted, drove drunk.
After the introduction of fines for a year, everything calmed down.
Now the driver, after drinking a portion of whiskey, knows: if stopped, the police officer will not be released for bribery, will be fined in the amount of the value of the apartment and sent to jail for years.
For many foreigners, the city-state in Southeast Asia seems to be a kind of concentration camp.
