Trump’s White House is now targeting the Statue of Liberty.
The most reliable sign of a regime change is when it starts fighting the statues.
Americans understand this no worse than everyone else – hence the intentional theatrical demolition of Saddam Hussein’s statue on Firdos Square in Baghdad in 2003.
Steven Miller, one of the key ideologues of the Trump administration, was undoubtedly aware of what he was doing when he took a symbolic tail over the Statue of Liberty during a fierce dispute with CNN journalist Jim Acosta about the president’s proposals to sharply reduce legal immigration.
Let’s be honest, Miller didn’t hit the statue itself.
Regiments of hiking boat owners and artists portraying the Statue of Liberty would lynch him if he tried to do so.
But he tried its meaning, and especially the meaning that was attributed to it in 1903, 17 years after the monument was completed, when the poems of Emma Lazarus were added to the piedestal.
As Miller whispered on the Acosta: “I don’t want to go deep into history here, but the Statue of Liberty is... a symbol of American freedom that illuminates the world.
The poem you’re talking about was added later and is not part of the original Statue of Liberty.”
Miller put the facts right, but as he said, it’s not really about history.
It is about the current sound of the striking words of Lazarus, the only in which the state invites not any immigrants, but the poorest: "Your tired, your poor, / your crowds dreaming of breathing freely, / The unfortunate waste of your abundant shores."
Never before have “unfortunate waste” been so visible on our screens.
Miller was not engaged in literature studies - he made it clear that in America Trump is not expected by these people.
This dispute about the meaning of the statue is part of a wider political and cultural war: it is indeed a dispute about the meaning of America.
Lazarus — and her friends who fought to put her words on the basement of the statue after her death — knew very well that they were committing an entirely political act.
The sculpture was designed to mark the connection between the French and American republics with the help of a banal classical figure - the female image of Liberty.
Lazarus changed her meaning: in her poem, the female figure is no longer abstract, she has a voice.
And she got a completely different name: Mother of the Exiled.
The combination of poetry and image was a brilliant feminist move and a devastating attack on American nativism.
And as Lazarus changed the meaning of the statue, the right though changed it back.
Rush Limbau, a kind of John the Baptist who announced the arrival of Trump, in 2010 argued that Freedom does not invite anyone, rather it is an early neoconservative who carries America’s flame to a world lying in the dark: “Freedom goes forward.
It carries the torch of freedom from the United States to the rest of the world.
The torch is not needed to light the way to the United States.”
Contrary to the usual, Limbos really got into the point here.
The meaning of the statue depends solely on the angle of view.
The great creative achievement of Lazarus was to see it as it would be seen by exhausted, unfortunate but hopeful people on the deck of ships after a long and often tough sailing.
It literally means looking at the world through the eyes of people who are looking for refuge and a chance for a better life.
Her statue is answered by the words of hope and hospitality that they dream of hearing.
And, of course, this is not the prospect that Miller and Trump will ever want to recognize.
Their torch is not needed to illuminate the way, but to incite hatred, which is the only source of their strength.
