Blocking critics on Facebook: Don’t run for public office if you’re not ready to listen to criticism from voters
The founder of our country understood what a critical press is.
Americans loved George Washington, but that didn’t stop them from criticizing him for everything from domestic politics to his political principles.
Criticism annoyed him.
But he did not shut his mouth to his critics.
Because in 1783 Washington said: “Freedom of speech can be taken away and we, the deaf and the dumb, will be led like sheep to slaughter.”
Now I’ll go to Maryland Governor Larry Hogan, who should try to look more like Washington.
Hogan's subordinates blocked and deleted posts of at least 450 people who expressed their opinions on his official Facebook page.
This week, the American Civil Liberties Union filed a lawsuit against him.
The governor's subordinates called the lawsuit null and the commentary on the Internet was written in the spirit of "well and what".
“It’s just Facebook,” many will say.
But it is also important.
And this is especially important when it comes to a guy like Hogan.
He is a surprisingly popular Republican governor in a predominantly democratic state.
He is in second place in the rating of approval among 50 governors of the country.
Hogan is not a stubborn reactionary.
He demonstrated a strong hand in state management and a commitment to his principles.
He also skillfully uses Facebook as his primary way of communicating with his voters and jokingly shows his bald head on his page after chemotherapy.
Therefore, blocking people who come to the governor’s page – which is stated as an official public forum and is run by administration officials for taxpayers’ money – is unnecessary and ultimately harmful.
In an interview with the Washington Post, spokeswoman Amelia Ches defended the governor’s actions, arguing that blocking comments was just moderation.
But it’s too easy – to use the image of trolls, spammers, and hackers who are wicked on the internet.
The Post spoke with some of the real people who were blocked by Hogan.
And these are real people, not trolls, teachers, businessmen, pastors, who turn to their chosen leaders.
They all say that their comments were respectful, meaningful and not rude.
The pastor quoted the Bible, appealing to the fact that Hogan was a Catholic.
Laxmi’s lawyer Sarma Ramana from Bowie, Maryland, did not express hatred but asked about hate crimes.
“I wrote a polite comment that I am disappointed by his lack of reaction to hate crimes and other recent news,” she wrote in the post.
"I also don't like the idea that when many people leave comments on the same topic, some immediately say it's a so-called twist instead of admitting they're dealing with a large group of dissatisfied citizens."
What the governor’s subordinates call a “centric spam attack,” others would probably call an “active life position.”
In the era of Facebook, it’s easy to sub-edit your image by simply blocking critics or wiping out negative comments.
This is much less dusty work than it used to be when it required sending people, collecting and burning newspapers with critical headlines, or arresting and clogging the mouths of protesters.
But that’s exactly what’s happening now, only in numbers.
Hogan is not the first official to be criticized for not listening to Facebook and other social networks.
President Trump has been sued by Twitter users who were banned in his Twitter account.
One of the first turnaround decisions on this topic was made this week in Virginia.
According to the U.S. District Judge from Alexandria, James K. Kasheris, Laudon County Chairman of the Supervisory Board violated the First Amendment by hacking a voter on his Facebook account.
And in Kentucky, Republican Governor Matt Bevin has been sued by the American Civil Liberties Union for his behavior on Facebook and Twitter.
It should not be so difficult.
In Washington’s time, the era of affordable postal expenses made roughly the same turnaround as the Internet today.
From 1776 to 1800, the number of newspapers quadrupled, and the authors of anonymous letters severely undermined his authority.
Even then, Washington was dealing with anonymous trolls.
People under the pseudonyms “Juricola”, “Valerius”, “Belizarius” and “Portius” wrote letters to newspapers that ridiculed Washington’s decision.
According to historical documents collected by the online George Washington Documents project, his office has been overwhelmed by petitions criticizing his position on the Treaty on Friendship, Trade and Navigation.
But he did not try to silence them.
Freedom of speech, dissent and expression is the very foundation of our state.
And true leadership means agreeing to it.
