Poverty and death in Indonesia’s “golden land”
While cooking lunch, Bardeen Degey does not use the plate.
She even rarely uses bad.
In her wooden house in Enarotali, the capital of Panay County in the rebellious Indonesian province of Papua, the housewife usually just puts a sweet potato, which is called a “note” here, right into the fireplace.
After half an hour, the bulbs are taken and eaten with impatient, unwashed hands.
Degee sits on the ground floor — she has no furniture — and here she does her homework, such as washing clothes with muddy water from a nearby mud.
The bathroom serves as a cage in a room without a roof.
She is the youngest of her husband's four wives, so she was not instructed to work in the field.
Multitasking is widespread here.
Of course, working late can be dangerous: many men from this village are unemployed, many drink, and there are soldiers.
“Nobody dares to walk around the village after five o’clock,” she says.
It is a rare opportunity to look at everyday life in the high mountains of Papua, a former Dutch colony that was annexed to Indonesia in 1969 after a questionable referendum, when only 1026 elders were forced to vote, publicly raising their hands before the occupying troops.
The existing movement for independence from the Netherlands has quickly turned its anger against the government of Jakarta, whichins tight control over the region, preventing foreign journalists and human rights activists.
In 2003, the province was officially divided into Papua and West Papua, and the independent state of Papua New Guinea occupies the eastern part of the island.
Enarotali is a city as remote as it is abandoned; the road here includes a one-and-a-half-hour flight from Jaapura, the administrative center of the province, to Naber, and then a five-hour rush in a rental car.
There is no public transport here.
The city, with a population of about 19,000, consists of wooden houses surrounded by bamboo fences; the roofs of wooden steel are painted with rust in a variety of redish shades.
Few Indonesians arrived here, not to mention journalists, and almost no foreigners.
Prior to the arrival of the Christian missionaries, the Papuan Mee Pago worshipped a god named Uga Tamee.
