Papua is Indonesia’s poorest province, with 28% of its population living below the poverty line, and child mortality and literacy levels among the worst in Asia.
This is Indonesia’s golden land.
The world’s largest and most lucrative gold mine, Grasberg, owned by Phoenix-based Freeport McMoran, is just sixty miles from Panay, a high-mountain province about the size of New Jersey, where 153,000 people live.
Freeport produced gold and copper for approximately $3.1 billion in 2015.
In addition, Papua boasts forest reserves estimated at $78 billion.
These riches, however, entail one misfortune for the Papuas, ensuring that the powerful armed forces of Indonesia maintain their suffocating presence here.
According to a 2005 investigation by the New York Times, between 1998 and 2004, Freeport paid local soldiers and units $20 million, including up to $150,000 to one officer.
Demands for greater autonomy by the Papuas threaten the existence of this golden veil and are ruthlessly suppressed.
According to human rights activists, more than 500,000 Papuan have been killed by Indonesian military forces since 1969, and thousands more have been raped, tortured and imprisoned.
According to the Asian Commission on Human Rights, the mass killings in the indigenous high mountains of Papua in the 1970s can be considered a genocide.
Last year alone, Indonesian police arrested more than 3,900 peaceful protesters in the region.
“We will lose everything,” a report published in 2016 by the diocese of Brisbane, contains evidence of atrocities committed in the previous year, such as executions without trial, torture – frequent, as claimed in another report, rape and electric shock – and brutal suppression of peaceful demonstrations.
“It’s hard to count the number of victims because incidents happen every week,” says Andreas Harsono, an Indonesian researcher for Human Rights Watch.
The hikes were delayed as Papua's resources attracted the influx of displaced people from other parts of Indonesia.
The 3,5-million population of the province is 83 percent Christian, but demographics change as Muslim economic migrants arrive from the densely populated Indonesian islands of Java, Sumatra and Sulawesi.
Javanese shops, "varung", sell fried chicken and a mixture of vegetables "gado-gado", served with peanut sauce.
The locals are trying to withstand the competition.
