Indonesian President Joko Widodo, popularly known as Djokovic, vowed to address inequalities and rights abuses in Papua during his 2014 presidential campaign.
On his way to the Presidential Palace in Jakarta, the former carpenter gained support from 27 of Papua’s 29 districts, including Panaya.
But almost nothing has changed in Papua, and the locals feel dedicated.
“Our hearts are broken because in 2014 we voted for Djokovic, expecting him to fulfill our hopes of restoring justice,” Jo said.
In fact, only two months after Djokovic's October inauguration, Panay survived a tragedy.
On December 7, 2014, a group of 11 children were on the street singing the Christmas hymns at a fire in Enarotali when two Indonesian soldiers on a motorcycle escaped from the dark.
The frightened children told them that they should turn on the lights.
According to local pastor Javed Tebay, one of the soldiers was offended by their tone and returned after a while with four soldiers.
According to the victims and eyewitnesses, the soldiers who were drunk were chasing the children and beating them with rifles.
Then one of the soldiers shot at a group of children.
One child, sixteen-year-old Julian Aimo, was so badly beaten that he fell into a coma.
A few hours later, someone set fire to the nearby government building of the election commission, and the next day the situation worsened.
Around a thousand Papuan men, women and children gathered on a football field in front of a local police station and military command center to demand justice.
They brought with them ritual hunting bows and performed wita, a dance of the Papuan Mee Pago tribe: they ran in circles and depicted bird singing.
Some protesters started throwing stones at a police station and a military base.
When the situation escalated, the internal radio communications soldiers were ordered, “If the crowd resisted more than three times, shoot them,” as it sounded, as claimed in an official document, which was seen by Times correspondents, but which was not published in local media.
Fifty-six-year-old Jeremias Kaiame, the head of the Kego Coto district in Enarotali, felt the danger approaching and called for calm, asking the crowd to walk around the houses.
No one wanted to listen to him.
“When I turned, a bullet suddenly hit my left wrist,” he told Time magazine, standing on the doorstep of his brightly painted wooden house.
Kaiame still does not know who fired, but says the bullet arrived from the side of the square of gathered soldiers.
“There was a crowd, there were many shots,” he added.
The local resident Alfius Yove was hit three times, according to his cousin, who witnessed the shooting.
“I ran to him and examined his body to make sure it was him,” said Johannes, who, like many Indonesians, uses only one name.
“I saw that he was dead... I kissed him.”
General Yotje Mende, the senior inspector of Papua police, told reporters that his officers were simply “defending” their base because it was being attacked.
“We have to defend ourselves when people threaten to kill us,” Papuan police spokesman Commissary Pudjo Sulissio said in 2015.
“It is a question of life and death.”
According to Human Rights Watch, five young protesters were killed and many more were wounded.
The news of the murders reached Jakarta only the next day.
Three weeks later, Djokovic delivered a fierce speech in Jaapura, in which he expressed his condolences to the families of the victims and vowed to address the issue of historic abuse of power in Papua.
“I want this situation to be settled immediately so that it never happens again in the future,” he said.
In October 2016, the security minister said he would set up a non-judicial organization to put an end to historic human rights violations.
The excuses came almost immediately.
Most of the violations have occurred for a long time.
Some of them took place in the nineties or at the beginning of the zero.
The fact is that we, of course, want to deal with these violations, but there are procedures that need to be passed," he said.
Viranto then gave up his words, speaking to Time magazine on June 5 in Jakarta, and said he did not plan to set up an organization to handle complaints in Papua.
Instead, he said, “Everything will be decided through the court.”
Viranto, who was accused by the United Nations of “crimes against humanity” in connection with the deaths of more than 1,000 people during the bloody independence vote in East Timor in 1999, said 11 human rights violations in Papua had already been settled, including the Panaya incident.
The families of the victims from Panaya have met such statements with dark suspicion.
“Over the past three years I’ve been questioned four times, but there’s been absolutely no change,” says Johannes.
“I am tired.”
He says that years later he still lives in fear.
“I am scared,” he says.
“I am afraid that the military will arrest me, I am afraid that I will be shot.”
His brother Jacobus also expressed the opinion that the inhabitants of Panay are afraid to discuss the incident.
He said he was beaten by the military after helping to bury four victims.
