“I was hiding at home for two days.”
The Deiyai Parliament demanded that the officers involved in the incident be called for response, and the mobile police brigade be withdrawn from the region.
Panya has always been a sick place for the Indonesian government.
The lack of significant development causes dissatisfaction among the Meiji, Monini, Dani and Damal tribes, scattered throughout the greenery of the central high mountainous areas of Papua.
Many have joined the Papua Free Movement (OPM), a rebel army that claims to defend the rights of the Papuan people by organizing sporadic attacks and raids with kidnapping of Indonesian soldiers.
Some of OPM’s top executives come from Panaya, including Tadius Yogi and Daniel Yudas Kogoya.
In retaliation, thousands of people have been arrested and unjustified by the military in Panaya in recent years under the pretext of “defending national independence.”
Some have never returned.
Among the population, Papua Panaya is considered “a sad, forgotten place.”
Poverty increases dissatisfaction.
