According to Felim Kine, deputy director for Asia at Human Rights Watch, Jokov’s campaign promises to lift restrictions on media work in order to promote transparency and development have not been fulfilled.
“Now foreign journalists trying to report from rebellious eastern Indonesian provinces, Papua and West Papua, are facing new dangers: visa refusal and blacklisting,” he said in a statement.
The lack of attention from the press means that international pressure on the Indonesian government is largely limited to Papua’s immediate neighbors.
In March, six Pacific states – Tonga, Nauru, Palau, Tuvalu, Marshall Islands and Solomon Islands – appealed to the UN Human Rights Council to investigate “varied and widespread violations” in Papua, including the Panaya shooting.
The same countries have supported OPM in the past.
