EPA chief Pruitt rejects intention to postpone implementation of Obama’s emissions reduction rules
The day after 15 states filed a lawsuit, the head of the Environmental Protection Agency canceled his decision to postpone the implementation of Obama’s rules aimed at reducing emissions of air pollutants and smog-causing substances.
Pruitt explained his decision by the fact that now his agency is larger than in previous administrations, listening to the needs of the environmental regulators of individual states.
He did not mention a lawsuit against his previous position filed with the Federal Court of Appeal.
The dispute revolved around the deadline on October 1, by which the states must ensure compliance with 2015 ozone standards on the ground level.
In June, Pruitt announced that he would postpone their observance by one year to give his department more time to study the plan and avoid "disagreement with local decisions or obstacles to economic growth."
Pruitt, who was Oklahoma’s Attorney General before being appointed by President Trump to his current position, has long been known as a consistent opponent of tightening environmental regulations.
After moving to Washington, Pruitt repeatedly blocked or postponed the introduction of regulations that were opposed by the chemical or gas-oil industries.
The unexpected change of course on Wednesday is another legal defeat of Pewitt’s course to return to the previous norms.
Last month, a federal appeal court in Washington ruled that the EPA chief exceeded his powers in an attempt to postpone the implementation of the Obama administration’s rule requiring oil and gas companies to track and reduce methane leaks.
In a statement released on Wednesday evening, Pruitt suggested that by sharply changing the course of ozone standards, he was simply fulfilling the EPA’s obligation to cooperate with the states in a comprehensive process of timely implementation of the new standards.
“Under previous administrations, the EPA was often unable to meet the deadlines, then awaited lawsuits from groups of activists and other individuals and discussed deadlines in the settlement of the case,” said Pruitt, who filed more than a dozen lawsuits against the EPA in his previous position.
“We do not believe in regulation through court proceedings, and we take the deadlines seriously.
We also take our charter and the power it gives us seriously.”
However, the EPA statement said that Pruitt could at some point again use its “delaying powers and other given by law powers” to make sure that the rules “jcyjdfys on a clear course and on all available information.”
Republicans in Congress are insisting on a broader revision of ozone regulations.
The bill, approved by the House of Representatives last month, aims to postpone the implementation of 2015 rules for at least eight years.
The Senate has not yet voted on the matter.
New York Attorney General Eric Schneiderman, who headed the coalition of states that filed a lawsuit against the EPA this week, said the group intended to continue legal pressure.
“The EPA change – after our lawsuits – is an important victory in the struggle for the health and safety of 6.7 million New Yorkers and more than 115 million Americans directly affected by the smog covering their cities,” Schneiderman said.
The lawsuit of New York joined California, Connecticut, Delaware, Illinois, Iowa, Maine, Massachusetts, New Mexico, Oregon, Pennsylvania, Rhode Island, Vermont and Washington, as well as the District of Columbia.
Earth-level ozone occurs when ordinary pollutants from machinery, power plants, refineries and chemical plants and other sources react in the atmosphere with sunlight.
The resulting smog can cause serious breathing problems in sensitive people, leading to thousands of premature deaths a year.
Health advocates and environmentalists have welcomed the unexpected change in Pruitt’s course.
