71-year-old Brooks is a former congressman of Georgia who has fought for human rights all his life.
For him, the show is a dramatic call to action and an annual reminder to the Monroe residents that injustice has never been corrected.
“We want investigations, we want conclusions, we want healing, we want reconciliation, but first we have to get justice,” he said.
“We can’t move on to healing and reconciliation until we get justice.”
The coroner covers the body of one of the victims of the lynching at Morse Ford on July 27, 1946.
According to FBI materials received by NBC News, more than 50 people in Monroe and neighboring counties were suspected of involvement in lynching.
But no one has ever been charged.
Although the suspects have been on the lookout for decades, human rights activists say the city has always known the two connected motives of the lynchers: politics and sex.
In April 1946, a Supreme Court ruling for the first time allowed black citizens to vote for the primaries, which were to take place that summer.
About during the same election, according to FBI reports, the black exploiter Roger Malcolm struck in a knife fight Barnett Hester, a white landowner — apparently because of a woman.
Brooks says that, according to rumors spreading in the city, Hester slept with Malcolm Dorothy's wife, and that the child she was supposed to have was not from her husband.
According to FBI reports, on July 25, 1946, Lloyd Harrison, a large white landowner, paid a $600 bail to free Malcolm from prison.
He went to prison with Dorothy and their cousins May Murray and George Dorsey.
But as they drove out of prison and approached the Mors Ford Bridge, a crowd of lynchers surrounded the car.
"It is being established that Harrison organized and commanded the killings," a report from the FBI said.
“It is also obvious that there was a conspiracy between the law enforcement authorities of the state and the city, which not only took part in the killings, but also destroyed evidence and concealed the identities of witnesses.”
Brooks calls it shorter.
“It was an attempt at voting rights,” he said.
“They were all killed to send a signal to black people in the city: if you register and vote, you will be the same.”
For a decade, Cassandra Green has directed an annual show recreating the lynching at the Mors Ford Bridge.
Her performance is visible, it captures the viewer and tells about that profound racism that, as many would like to think, is no longer in America.
It’s hard to watch and even harder to turn away, but Green thinks that’s the main thing.
"We don't want to talk about Lynch's courts because they show us our own ugliness," she says.
“But I can’t build a relationship with you unless you hear me or hear what I’ve experienced.”
The rehearsals of this year’s play began in June, and on the first day almost 30 actors – a dozen white, the rest black – gathered in the room and listened to the review of the play shredded over the years.
Wade Marbo was the director along with Green.
He played the role of the chief member of the clan for several years, but says the role has never become easier.
“I feel like I’ve gotten upset because it’s not the person I am,” says Marbo.
“But I think it’s very important to remember this story because we don’t want to go back to that time.”
In the room, the actors Darrius Bradshaw and Nick Rascone, who play Roger Malcolm and Barnett Hester, repeat their roles.
The show begins with Malcolm, angry that Hester is sleeping with his wife Dorothy, shouting and pushing him.
“I said, nigga, get out of my house!”
I scream in response.
A blow is given.
And at the same time, everyone (at least all black actors) is reflected in a whistle.
Green laughed louder.
“What is it?” asks Ascon.
He is worried and embarrassed.
Am I overplaying?
“No,” Greene said through laughter.
“I just don’t think white people said ‘nigga’ at the time.”
“Yes,” laughs one of the black performers.
“You have to make a hard ‘r’.”
And the energy in the room also changes: discomfort is replaced by a sense of companionship.
Everyone must do everything right, not only for the sake of the play, but also for the memory of four killed people.
The scene begins again.
This time, when Rascona says the word on the letter "n", it turns out to be clear and sharp.
No one laughs.
The show ends violently and quickly.
Cries, shots and then silence.
A woman in mourning black clothes stands over the bodies of the actors and performs Billy Holiday's sad song "Strange Fruit".
Her voice was interrupted by a word.
A hundred yards from it, half a hundred spectators wipe away tears and sweat from their eyes.
There are almost equal numbers of black and white spectators.
A couple came from Itaca, New York to watch the show; many live nearby.
They all endured the heavy blow of Georgia for almost eight hours, while Brooks led them on a pilgrimage to the graves of Malcolm and Dorsey.
Until then, the murders were only history, but now, as they stand in the same place where they lynched people, it seems that their ghosts are in the air.
When the last note of the song is silenced, Green invites people to come closer and examine the bodies.
The children bend to their heads, touch the paint depicting blood, and fixed bodies, and whisper something to each other.
“They’re not really dead,” a little boy cried out, as if to remind himself of it.
After a few minutes, Green thanked the spectators, and suddenly it was over.
The actors throw off ropes from their necks and wipe their tears.
Bradshaw embraces Marbo, a man in a costume who played the main doll clown.
Nick Rascona hugs two other actors and suddenly, crying, falls into their arms: the emotional load of the show finally fell on him.
“Everything is fine,” a woman whispered.
“We know your heart is good.
You had a reason for that.”
Later, the spectators sit down for dinner with the actors.
At one table, a white couple from Atlanta lively discusses a show with a black couple they just met.
Denisa Daplinsky struggles to find words to describe what she feels after the show.
“It’s hard to listen to those horrible, horrible words and actions... people who look like you and who do it because they look like you,” she says.
“After that, I think that lynching is still happening,” she adds, “only now it’s called that the police are shooting.”
In the other corner of the room, the general attention was taken by Tyran Brooks, who recalls his work as a human rights activist after a meal.
He says he has already begun planning a show next year.
“The show inspires us because it not only describes the horror of what we’ve experienced, it also teaches us,” he says.
"Because if you don't learn from this lesson, it can happen again.
Those who do not study their history, who do not know their history, are doomed to repeat it.”
