New results for assessing the age of asylum seekers in Sweden
The latest results of tests of asylum seekers in Sweden who have been subjected to the new medical method of age assessment show that more than 80 percent of respondents were assessed as persons over the age of 18, but not all trust the accuracy of these results.
The Swedish National Agency for Forensic Medicine (Rättsmedicinalverket) began conducting tests earlier this year.
They were designed to make the age assessment in the asylum process more accurate after the Swedish Migration Agency (Migrationsverket) was criticized for failing to determine the actual age of some refugees who claimed to be minors.
To date, Migrationsverket has sent 6,880 cases for testing, and the forensic agency has now published the results of 2,481 tests for the period between mid-March and 31 July 2017.
Eighty percent (2002) of the test subjects were estimated to be people 18 years or older, and in another 25 cases the forensic agency estimated that the test subjects were “probably a person 18 years or older.”
In the case of 432 cases, the conclusion was that the person was “probably under 18”.
Tests are carried out only in cases where the age of the person causes doubts.
According to Johan Geranson of the Forensic Medicine Agency, the results are consistent with the results of previous months.
"We don't see much difference with the statistics for the past months, the numbers are quite relevant," he told The Local.
The high percentage of cases in which people were assessed as having reached the age of 18 does not necessarily indicate that asylum seekers lied about their age.
In May, the agency published the results of 581 tests and that in 442 cases, “the most likely age of the tested is 18 years or more.”
However, after examining the 581 published results, the newspaper "Svenska Dagbladet" found that in 243 cases a man openly stated that he was 18 this year.
The method of conducting a medical assessment of age, consisting of making x-rays of wisdom teeth and tomography of knee joints and giving them for analysis to dentists and radiologists, has also caused criticism in some instances.
One of the skeptics is an endocrinologist from the Carolina Institute, Claude Marcus, part of whose work is to assess the biological maturity of people in order to determine whether they have gone through puberty earlier or later than usual.
“I had reason to think about it, and I don’t think we should use the methods of measurement that are being used now.
The biological age is thus determined very inaccurately.
If we can’t identify it with certainty, we shouldn’t pretend we can,” he told Metro.
However, Geranssen of the forensic agency spoke in favor of the accuracy of the tests: “In general, we can say that the risk is wrong to take a child for an adult is small.
We face the greatest risk when a person is soon 18, in which case it is about 10 percent.”
