Starting in September, patients will get access to a “revolutionary” drug for HIV prevention after a battle in the High Court over funding the drug from the State Health Service.
The National Health Service of England has announced that pre-exposure HIV prevention (PREP), a pill taken before sex that has been shown to reduce the risk of infection in individuals at risk by an average of 86 percent, will now be provided by the health service over an initial three-year trial period of approximately 10,000 people.
She agreed to fund the trial after the Court of Appeal backed a High Court ruling last year claiming that the National Health Service had the ability to pay the PrEP despite her claims that it should be funded by the local authorities.
The move, which was announced on Thursday, was called a “most important innovation” by the president of the National Health Service of England, Simon Stevens, and the National Agency for AIDS Control (NAT) called it a “turning point.”
Before the full launch of the program across England by April 2018, venereal clinics in London, Brighton, Manchester, Liverpool and Sheffield will be among the first to start registering people, and even more clinics will join the program in October.
Pre-exposure prevention (PREP) is a course of HIV drugs taken before sex to reduce the risk of HIV infection.
As studies have shown, PrEP significantly reduces the risk of HIV infection among people at risk.
When taking PrEP before sex in the human body a sufficient amount of certain drugs to prevent HIV infection.
Such drugs can be taken daily or no later than two hours before sex.
Patients eligible for the drug include homosexual and bisexual men, transgender men and people whose partners are HIV-positive and do not receive successful treatment.
Dispensers will select suitable participants who have agreed to participate in the study, including men, women, transgender people and individuals whose partners are unknown if their HIV status is constrained by antiretroviral therapy.
People living and attributed to a general practitioner in England will also be able to apply for potential participation in the nearest venereal dispensary participating in the program.
The program will cost £10 million, and the National Health Service of England signed a contract this week after an international tender for the drug.
The study is designed to evaluate all the possibilities of PrEP through the collection of clinical data on who is the target audience of the drug, its digestibility and its use on a large scale.
“This key innovation should complement and strengthen the widespread and increasingly successful efforts to prevent HIV.
This is another milestone in more than three decades of success in combating one of the biggest health threats facing humanity.
Deborah Gold, president of NAT (National Agency for AIDS Control), said: “This is a turning point in the fight against HIV.
PrEP, if it is properly targeted at people in need and at risk, gives the opportunity to change the situation with the HIV epidemic in England.
Starting in September, people at risk for HIV, thanks to this study conducted in England on behalf of the National Health Service, will have access to a new opportunity-opening remedy, the use of which a person can control themselves without discussing it with a partner, which will lead to improving many, many lives.
We warmly welcome this news.”
Ian Green, president of the Terrence Higgins Foundation, said: “Now the first thing we need to do is make sure that the trial quickly spreads across the country and that no one at risk for HIV is forgotten.
Now that we are provided with the experimental PrEP drug, we are going to protect more than 10,000 people who are at risk for HIV.”
Shadow Public Health Minister Sharon Hodgson said: “We very much welcome the start of the PrEP test, it was very late due to months of delays and government wires.”
The data shows how revolutionary this drug can be as part of our approach to preventing HIV and stopping the transmission of this fatal infection.
This test will bring us one step closer to fully understanding the benefits of PrEP.
It is now important that the trial be deployed across the country as soon as possible to protect people at risk for HIV and to move us one step further towards stopping the spread of HIV in society.
