The judges are offered to protect from the presidents
The Presidential Council on Human Rights (CPHR) on behalf of Vladimir Putin has developed proposals to strengthen the independence of the judicial branch of power.
The CPI proposes to limit the powers of the presidents of the courts and introduce their eligibility.
For the courts of appeal and cassation instances, the SPL wants to introduce special districts that will not be attached to the administrative-territorial division in the Russian Federation.
The Supreme Court must also submit its proposals within the presidential mandate.
The CPJ has completed the development of proposals that will strengthen the independence of the Russian judiciary.
This work was carried out on the order of Vladimir Putin from January 3, 2017, which the President gave after a meeting with members of the council.
At the meeting with the members of the council on 8 December 2016, individual cases of judicial arbitration, as well as problems of public control in places of imprisonment of citizens were discussed (see "Ъ" of 9 December).
The result of the work of the CPJ was 25 proposals, which concern both the issues of ensuring the independence of judges and the identification of judicial errors, as well as the financing of courts and legal education.
One of the ideas of the Kremlin human rights activists is to limit the powers of the presidents of the courts to increase the independence of the other judges.
If the candidate for the position of a judge successfully passed the competition and received the support of the judge community, then the chairman of the court, in the opinion of the CPJ, should present him for appointment, without having the right to refuse, as this is permitted now by the law.
It is also proposed to deprive the chairman of the right to distribute cases for consideration between judges.
To do this, experts allow, can specially written computer program.
The Chairman has no right to "predetermine the results of the qualification of the judge, to initiate his disciplinary responsibility, to make decisions on the establishment of additional material payments".
At the same time, the presidential council considers it necessary to move to the "election of the presidents of the courts by the judges themselves" and "allocate their powers for a comparatively short period with mandatory rotation".
Currently, all Chairmen of courts (from republican to district) are appointed for six years by the President on the proposal of the Chairman of the Supreme Court of the Russian Federation.
In order to protect judges from pressure from regional administrations, the CPI proposes to organize appeal and cassation in courts of general jurisdiction in a new way.
Now their structure is linked to the administrative-territorial division in the Russian Federation.
It is necessary to ensure the organization of individual courts of appeal and cassation instances not at the level of regional judicial bodies in the subjects of the Russian Federation, but in judicial districts.
The experts are based on the practice of arbitration courts.
There are "judicial districts" that do not coincide with the administrative division in the Russian Federation, but guarantee at the expense of this greater independence from regional officials who are difficult to use the "telephone right".
The CPJ proposes that the world judges be strengthened by people’s seats to consider with their participation some “categories of civil and administrative cases”.
For example, deprivation of parental rights, restoration at work, protection of honor and dignity, deprivation of driving licenses, etc.
"These are only our proposals," explained "Ъ" member of the SPC, the retired judge of the Constitutional Court, Tamara Morshchakov.
She also recalled that the mandate of the president applied not only to the Supreme Court, but also to the Supreme Court, which has not yet disclosed its proposals.
Time for the execution of the assignment by the Armed Forces (among the co-executors - the Prosecutor General and the Commissioner for Human Rights in the Russian Federation) is still there.
To report to Vladimir Putin on how effectively the independence of the judiciary is ensured in the Russian Federation, the Chairman of the Armed Forces Vyacheslav Lebedev must before September 1.
Living a High Life: A Half Floor and Delicious Design Techniques Turn This Small Apartment In Earl's Court Into A Spatial Home
Joanne Lee, a former real estate bankier, moved from a spacious house in Knightsbridge to an apartment in Earl's Court in 2014.
The apartment is on the first floor of a cute typical Queen Anne house, and in favor of the new design says that Joan has not picked up her things and has not moved again.
“I previously lived with my ex in Knightsbridge on a much larger area,” says Joan.
“I was looking for something comparable for my money.
I was shown this apartment in Earl’s Court, and there were the same high ceilings.
I fell in love with her and offered the price the same day.”
From the moment of the first view, the apartment with an area of 1000 square feet has undergone a complete reconstruction.
It was originally a one-bedroom apartment with a complex layout – to get into the bedroom, you had to go through the kitchen – and Joanna wanted to add storage space and a half-floor to get the most out of the generous height of the ceilings.
“I wanted high ceilings, big windows, lots of light.
Those were my demands,” she said.
For this purpose, she hired Erfan Azadi from Notting Hill’s Duck & Shed architectural and design studio to use 12.5-foot ceilings and create a home that would not only be a successful project, but would fit Joan’s life.
The ceiling was not high enough to accommodate two rooms above each other, so the architectural task was to create a half-floor where you could stand in full height.
Erfan had to think creatively to cope with the brief.
“Working with steel structures is very difficult,” he explains.
“We needed to arrange the rooms so that they were one above the other and didn’t have to bend.
It was necessary not just to build a simple platform, but to bend the structures so that they are at the right height and allow the space to be used from above and below.”
This decision allowed Erfan to arrange two full-size rooms one above the other in the dedicated space - and a lot more interesting.
From the ground floor through the vintage copper light window from "Retrouvius" is a view of the elegant living room below.
Mirror furniture with gold finish, silver accents and vintage lighting devices from Serzh Muya set the style of the project.
The use of mirrors plays a role in adding spectacularity, space and light.
A short corridor is framed with mirrors to make it seem longer.
In the kitchen, the mirror protective panel looks like a window into another room.
At the entrance, the mirror cabinets serve to store all Joan’s dishes.
To create a sense of more luxurious space, the beauty of the living room can overwhelm the kitchen when it is not used.
There is nothing new in the kitchen.
The singularity of this kitchen is that it is a shifting upward door, like in a garage.
“Here was engaged engineering art,” Erfan tells us about a wooden-fiber shield door armored with steel.
“It’s equipped with a counterweight, so when you push the door up, it slips very easily.”
Through the reasonable use of space and storage space, Joan received an additional 16 square meters, an additional bedroom and an improved layout.
“Ultimately, the floor area is exactly what you’re going to sell, that is, what your property is valued by,” Erfan says.
“Roughly speaking, the real estate agent will come in and make calculations based on the area of the sexes.”
Here they were able to increase the floor area, using high-quality materials that give the space a shade of luxury.
“Materials are what we touch, so they help create an emotional connection with the home,” Erfan says.
“No one falls in love with electrical wiring in the walls.
It’s important, but it doesn’t touch the strings of our hearts.”
This serves as a testimony to the fact that due to good design and increased metering the apartment can turn from something ordinary to something stunning.
In fact, like Joan, you can choose to stay.
