Brothers Fight for $500 Million Real Estate Empire
Two brothers fight for one of Victoria’s largest empires in real estate trade worth more than $500 million – forty years after their Italian ancestors founded the dynasty.
Former Carlton Football Club director and developer Colin de Luthies lives in Turak Palace through three doors from his younger brother Paul, who filed a lawsuit against him in the Supreme Court for the division of possessions and assets.
Paul wants to quit the family business since 2014, but the Supreme Court is still in a fierce dispute over the terms of the divorce.
Together with their mother, Anna, the brothers own 87 properties worth more than half a billion dollars, bought since their family bought a Smith Street store in 1973 in Collingwood.
There, the family founded Westco Jeans, which grew into a network of 160 stores.
It was sold in 1999 for $85 million.
The money was invested in real estate, and the list of possessions of the De Luthies family now includes office buildings, buildings in Brunswick and Sorrento, apartments on the Gold Coast and in Mount Buller, and shopping centers in the suburbs.
Under an agreement with his late father, Colin – whom Paul describes as the “main driving force and dominant personality” of the De Luthies family – owns about two-thirds of the company’s assets, while Paul owns about one-third.
According to the court, this means that Colin’s property is 316 million, and Paul’s – 176 million.
The division of property and money became a stumbling stone for Paul.
"The division proposed by Colin gives him, in my opinion, the best parts of the property," he wrote in his first testimony in 2015.
Last Friday, after several unsuccessful attempts to reconcile, the first hearing in the Supreme Court took place.
The brothers are now arguing about who will control the existing business – from which Paul believes Colin has excluded him.
Colin claims that this is not the case, but accuses Paul of incompetent management of some objects.
In the testimony Colin gave at the beginning of the trial, he says he hopes to resolve the dispute.
“My Italian roots make me consider seven a top priority,” he wrote.
Judicial costs are growing like a snowball: the case includes hundreds of pages of testimony, emails and reports from companies such as Deloitte, Pitcher Partners and Charter Keck Cramer; both sides have attracted the most famous lawyers, including the royal lawyer Alan Myers, and the finest strutters.
Ms. De Luthies and her late husband Luigi were immigrants from Italy; from the late 1950s they run dairy bars and gastronomies, and in the early 1970s they bought a store in Brunswick.
Under financial guarantees they bought a store in Collingwood, where Colin opened the first family jeans store.
Colin says he launched Westco when he was "in the last classes of school, and Paul was a boy then (about 10 years old)".
Anna De Lutis says she and Luigi, who died in 2012, hoped to pass on their possessions to their sons without conflict.
"Luigi has often told me that he doesn't want the brothers to go to court," she wrote.
Two other brothers, Mark and Luke, are no longer part of the De Lutis group of companies; Colina says Mark earned $10 million when he left the business, and Luke $26 million.
According to Paul, both Luke and Mark were “unhappy with the financial conditions of their department.”
Colin was not a public figure, although he was a former member of the board of directors of the AFL club and, according to Eddie McGuire's 2015 biography, the best friend of the television star.
Fairfax Media on Friday contacted Colin and Paul and their lawyers.
Colin only replied with a text message saying that since the case had not yet been considered in court, "I really have nothing to say."
“I’m very, very sorry that my brother Paul decided to file a lawsuit against me and shake the name of our family in court,” he wrote.
In mid-2016, Colin wrote in his testimony that he was trying to satisfy his brother’s demands.
“Our father’t want to see Paul and I argue in court,” he said, adding that “he’s still hoping for a solution to the conflict.”
On Friday, that hope seemed to have dissipated.
"The decision on our case will soon be made by the court," Colin wrote.
The new head of the Trump apparatus plans to limit the access of information to the president.
Others tried and were defeated.
Maybe John F. Kelly will really do it.
In that case, he will be the first.
