Tyumen Prosecutor's Office fights with HIV dissident
The Prosecutor’s Office challenged the ruling of the Kalininsky district court in Tyumen, which terminated the criminal case against a local resident, whose young daughter died from HIV.
According to the investigation, the child died because the mother is a HIV dissident and refused treatment.
However, the court released her from responsibility in connection with the reconciliation with the victim's father.
The Prosecutor’s Office believes that the crime cannot be left unpunished in order not to create a precedent for other HIV dissidents.
The case against the resident of Tyumen was initiated under part 1 of article 109 of the Criminal Code of the Russian Federation (causing death by negligence) in April - after her three-year-old daughter died from HIV-infection 4B stage.
According to the prosecutor’s office, the mother is HIV-infected.
"The woman did not treat herself and refused to treat her daughter, believing that there is no HIV infection," the Prosecutor's Office of the Tyumen region explained.
The criminal case entered the Kalininsky district court of Tyumen, which on July 25 decided on its termination.
The petition was filed by the father of the deceased girl, explaining that he "forgave his wife, has no claims to her, she smoothed the damage and apologized."
The Prosecutor’s Office did not agree with the court’s decision and filed an appeal, demanding to cancel the decision on the termination of the case and send it for a new consideration.
The girl died, and it is impossible to smooth out the damage caused by the crime.
The HIV-infected mother, contrary to the recommendations of doctors, refused to examine the baby and treat her from a dangerous infection,” the prosecutor’s office said.
According to the supervisory authority, she should be punished, otherwise other HIV dissidents will follow her example.
As told in the Tyumen AIDS Center, now in the Tyumen region about 12 children with HIV do not receive medical care due to the refusal of their parents.
"And this situation has already improved - in the year of the work of the special group, half of the parents who categorically refused to treat children from HIV, changed their mind - allowed to conduct a diagnosis, began to take drugs," - told the spokeswoman of the AIDS Center Elena Loseva.
According to her, it is impossible to influence parents in a legislative way, and as a result, not all HIV-infected children can be detected - mothers do not let them be examined, hide, escape with children from hospitals.
What are the dangers of HIV dissidents
At the end of last year, St. Petersburg sociologists presented the results of the first in Russia study of the so-called HIV dissident movement.
HIV dissidents are people who deny the existence of HIV and refuse to take medicines.
Doctors and activists of AIDS-service NGOs call such views anti-medical, and see their spread as a serious threat.
