Italy is tightening its tone against NGO ships rescuing migrants.
Italy has warned NGOs that own rescue vessels in the Mediterranean that they will not be able to continue working unless they comply with the new rules governing their activities.
“If non-governmental organizations do not comply with the new code of conduct, it is difficult to say whether they will be able to continue their activities,” Interior Minister Mario Minniti said in an interview with the Turin daily Stampa.
Minnit's warning came the day after Italian authorities seized a ship owned by the German humanitarian organization "Jugend Rettet" on suspicion that its crew actually cooperated with human traffickers and facilitated illegal immigration.
The humanitarian organization, which worked for only a year, declined to comment on the substance of the detailed charges raised against it by the Italian prosecutor Ambrogio Cartozio.
"For us, saving human lives is and will remain the highest priority, so we are very sorry that we cannot continue our activities in the search and rescue zone right now," the organization said in a statement.
"We will be able to assess all the allegations raised now only after we have gathered all the information and can evaluate the situation."
Italian authorities have been monitoring Juventus’s vessel, which belongs to Juventus Rettet, since October.
His crew is suspected of taking migrants on board with lifeboats that human traffickers sent directly to them and allowing smugglers to leave along with boats they could reuse.
At least one such encounter is believed to have taken place just 1.3 miles from the Libyan coast, according to the charges, which were published in Italian media.
The crew is suspected of violating the instructions of the Italian coastal authorities, which control rescue operations in the area, more for humanitarian sake than for any other reason.
The Code of Conduct implies, mainly, that vessels such as Juventus will have an Italian police officer on board to monitor their activities.
So far, only three of the nine NGOs involved in search and rescue operations have agreed to comply with the code: Save the Children, the Maltese MOAS and Pro-Activa Open Arms from Spain.
The latter said on Thursday that it considers the new rules unnecessary, but acceptable, provided they do not entail any “significant changes or obstacles” to its rescue operations.
Among those who refused to sign, is the Nobel Prize-winning organization Doctors Without Borders (MSF).
Meanwhile, Minniti said the sharp decline in the recent weeks in the number of migrants arriving in Italy as a result of rescue operations indicates that efforts to support the Libyan Coast Guard and cooperation with local mayors are yielding fruit.
“In recent days we have begun to see the light at the end of the tunnel,” the minister said.
He announced plans for further negotiations with Libyan mayors on economic development initiatives and with Chad, Niger and Mali on measures to reduce the number of migrants leaving these countries in the hope of reaching Europe.
“In Libya, we do not want to be associated with any of the parties to the conflict.
The authorities of the Russian Federation have recently markedly intensified their policy in the Libyan direction, and with visits to Moscow participated delegations of the opposing Libyan sides.
The head of the Russian contact group on the internal settlement of Libya at the Ministry of Foreign Affairs of the Russian Federation and the State Duma, the assistant of the head of the Chechen Republic, Lev Dengov told "Ъ", what goals Moscow pursues in this region and on whom it is betting.
Almost nothing is known about the Libya contact group you are leading.
Here, let’s say, the contact group on Ukraine – everyone knows about it.
Here is the curtain of secret.
What exactly do you do, what goals do you pursue?
The contact group was created at the initiative of the Russian Foreign Ministry and the State Duma.
Its activities are supervised by Deputy Foreign Minister Mikhail Bogdanov and Adam Delimhanov (Deputy of the Duma from Chechnya).
The latter is authorized to work in the Libyan direction by the Speaker of the State Duma Vyacheslav Volodin.
The impetus for the creation of the group was the detention in Libya of the Russian tanker "Mechanik Cheborarev" (in September 2015, there were 11 people on board. - "Ъ").
We thought about how to help the crew.
Then a contact group of military specialists, representatives of the State Duma was created, and our work was supported by Chechen leader Ramzan Kadyrov.
How did it happen that it was you who led it?
Since I have been working in Libya since 2008, I was asked to lead the group.
Our activities were not limited to the liberation of sailors from the Chebotarev Mechanic.
We managed to establish contacts with representatives of all the major groups facing each other in the Libyan conflict – both from Tripoli (where the UN-recognized government headed by Faiz Sarrazh is based) and Tobruk (the parliamentary residence that opposes the government and supports Marshal Khalifa Haftar, who controls the eastern regions of Libya).
Thanks to the active participation of Ahmed Metig (Vice Prime Minister of Libya - "Ъ"), we managed to quickly agree on the release of Russian sailors.
Then it was decided to create a contact group in order to use these contacts more effectively.
Its task is to analyze the situation, identify key factors and players, dialogue with all parties to the conflict.
I would like to emphasize in particular that in Libya we do not want to be associated with any of the parties to the conflict, we are in dialogue with all.
How many people are in the contact group and how many of them are permanently in Libya?
There are currently five people in the contact group.
Among them are people with experience working in force structures, including in the Ministry of Defense.
We also want to introduce a group of specialists for the region, representatives of the Institute of the Middle East of RAS.
No one of our employees is permanently in Libya, this is not necessary yet.
There are now Russian military advisors and instructors in Libya.
If so, on whose side?
There are no Russian military specialists in Libya.
All the talk and publication about this does not correspond to reality.
But in your contact group former military members are ...
And their presence is necessary.
For example, when we visit hot spots.
Or such cities closed up to a certain point for us, such as Misrata (where militia units are based, which played a role in the overthrow of Libyan leader Muammar Gaddafi in 2011 and markedly intensified in subsequent years).
We arrived in Missouri in January of this year.
We were frightened, they said that there were all Islamists, terrorists.
But it was important for us to evaluate the situation there, to analyze the real military potential, who is responsible for what, why there are such rumors, what is the role of Islamists.
In Misrata we met with all the representatives of the units that were engaged in the destruction of ISIS in Sirte (in December 2016 this city on the Mediterranean coast was captured by the militants of the banned in Russia “Islamic State” – “Ъ”).
We wanted to look at them, get acquainted with these people, check the information that they played a decisive role in the destruction of ISIS in Libya, and not Khalifa Haftar, who attributed these merits to himself.
And to what conclusion have you come?
Has the Islamic State defeated Haftar in Libya?
This was not he doing.
Haftar conducted operations on another front, in Benghazi.
And with ISIL in Sirte struggled structures subordinated to the government in Tripoli.
And, by the way, we invited people who conducted this anti-terrorist operation to Russia.
And they came - the visit lasted from 19 to 23 April this year, the Libyan delegation was received in the Federation Council, the Duma, the Foreign Ministry and the Rosgard.
As we understood, you are in all the Libyan regions and you probably imagine the mood of the local elites and field commanders.
Do you think it will be possible to implement the ceasefire agreements, the elections reached by Khalifa Haftar and Faiz Saraj in Paris in late July?
Or again, as has happened repeatedly in the past, agreements will be broken, hostilities will resume, the parties will try to seize power alone?
For us, a good signal was the fact that Sarage and Haftar agreed to another meeting, not so long ago it was impossible.
In the past, the two leaders have been extremely negative about each other.
As for Russia’s position...
They often write and say that Moscow actively supports Haftar, many believe in it.
We faced this situation when we were in Missouri, and Haftar was on board the Russian aircraft carrier Admiral Kuznetsov on that day.
It was coincidence.
But in Misrata they did not believe in coincidence.
We were told, “You are probably very brave people who came to us today.”
But our task is to show that we are not just supporting Haftar, we are in dialogue with all key parties in the conflict in Libya.
You and Haftar talked.
Does the fact that he studied twice in the USSR facilitate understanding with Russian partners on a human, emotional level?
And, by the way, does Haftar know Russian?
If he knows Russian, he is relatively good.
But what he learned from us, of course, facilitates the dialogue with him.
And not just with him.
When we talk to the military in Tripoli and Missouri, we meet generals who studied either in Russia or in the Soviet Union.
They speak Russian very well.
And they stretch to Russia, to some extent feel nostalgia for it.
Is it possible to lift the arms embargo imposed on Libya?
Are your Libyan interlocutors interested in Russian arms supplies?
They are interested, of course, but, as I said, we are not on one side in this conflict and we would not want to arm some at the expense of others.
We would like everyone to be in roughly equal positions.
As for the arms embargo, there are constant calls from the Libyans that Russia should somehow contribute to its lifting.
Currently, the process of drafting a constitution is actively progressing in Libya.
We hope that the parties will come to compromises and internal consensus.
Then elections should be held, as was discussed at the meeting between Sarajevo and Haftar.
If elections are held and the legitimate authority is finally elected (and now none of the parties has such status), then the issue of lifting the arms embargo can be raised in the UN Security Council.
To raise this question now is meaningless and dangerous, it will only lead to the escalation of the conflict.
Recently, the media that Italy, faced with the problem of African refugees floating from Libya, feels abandoned to the fate of its EU allies.
Can Moscow help Italian partners in this situation by using its ties with the Libyans?
How realistic, for example, is the possibility that Haftar’s troops will take control of the coast and put an end to the business of smugglers sending immigrants to Europe?
Very timely question.
We are actively working on this.
The Italians need the support of Russia, because Moscow is in dialogue simultaneously with Haftar, and with Sarajevo, and with Misrata, and with the south of the country.
And in this matter, the tribes in southern Libya play a big role, and they are ready to cooperate with Russia.
Is it about Southerners stopping the flow of migrants on long-distance approaches?
That is, conditionally speaking, the buses in which Nigerian migrants traveled were turned back?
We are achieving that.
But it is not easy.
Some clans and groups are interested in making these streams continue.
We hope to help unite the Southers in the negotiation process between Sarajevo, Haftar and the tribes of the South.
But first we would like to see the unity of opinion on this issue between Haftar and Sarage.
The head of government in Tripoli Faiz Saraj is considered an Islamist, a supporter of the introduction in the country of the norms of Sharia.
How radical is he?
Will this be an obstacle in building relations with Russia or the West?
I will give my personal opinion about him.
In my view, he is, on the contrary, an opponent of radical Islam.
Islamists are in the coalition.
Yes, but he himself holds the position that Libya should be an absolutely normal country – moderate Islam, open to the world.
He is also actively fighting terrorists.
Where did he get such a reputation?
It is created by those countries that are not interested in Russia communicating with Tripoli.
Tripoli is the capital, with legislative, executive and judicial powers.
There is the National Petroleum Corporation, the National Bank and other governmental structures.
Certainly, some countries were interested in not getting there.
And we mixed them all the cards and started to actively communicate with Tripoli and Tobruk.
And we are already reaping the fruits of this work: Rosneft has entered into a cooperation agreement with the state oil company of Libya - NOC.
NOC Director Mustafa Sanalla, with whom the head of Rosneft Igor Sechin concluded a deal, himself directly from Tripoli.
Two weeks ago, the first shipment of the Libyan oil company Rosneft took place.
What will Russia do with her?
I think to sell.
What are Russia’s economic interests in Libya?
The plan is to re-sign the contracts signed under Muammar Gaddafi.
We are talking, in particular, about previous agreements in the transport sphere (construction of railways), energy (electricity) and a number of others.
Do the Libyans have to pay?
They have oil.
That is, is it, as in the case of Iran, a scheme of "oil in exchange for services"?
I do not know what the scheme will be, I do not directly deal with these issues.
In fact, the economy for Russia in Libya is not the main thing.
We are actually working on peacekeeping.
For us, the main thing is to stop the bloodshed, to help the Libyans agree with each other so that they can establish order and Libya ceases to be a favorable environment for the development of terrorism.
For Russia, this is the main task of helping the Libyan people and pushing out the terrorists.
Do you have evidence of the presence in Libya (now or before) of radical militants from Russia or other countries of the former USSR?
One of the tasks of our contact group was to clarify this.
I met with a representative of the Libyan State Security Committee, who said that there is no one from Russia and other countries of the former USSR there.
He said he has about 50,000 recordings of telephone conversations of representatives of Islamist and radical groups (in Libya. - "Ъ") and Russian language does not sound there.
Which countries are these militants from?
I would not want to go into those details.
Then we formulate the question differently.
How many of the Islamist militants in Libya are Libyans themselves?
Libyans are virtually none among them, they are not more than 5%.
The rest are outdoors.
Can Moscow conduct intra-Libyan negotiations following the example of Paris?
There are such plans.
We are conducting active talks with the Libyans, several delegations from Libya have already visited Moscow, and have declared their readiness to come again - to Moscow or to Grozny.
When can such negotiations take place?
Now hard to say.
There are still several visits to be held, and then, I hope, there will be clarity about the time and place of the negotiations.
