Michelle Carter sentenced for reports that prompted Conrad Roy to commit suicide
A resident of Massachusetts was sentenced to two and a half years in prison for using text messages and phone calls to encourage suicide of her boyfriend Conrad Roy.
Michelle Carter, who is now 20 years old, will have to spend 15 months in jail and another 5 years of probation.
Carter was found guilty in June of the unintentional murder of Conrad Roy, who committed suicide on July 13, 2014.
Roy’s father said at a hearing on Thursday: “My family is murdered by sorrow.
My son was my best friend.”
Carter was allowed to remain free until appeal.
She was threatened with a maximum sentence of 20 years, but her lawyers said that both she and Roy suffered from mental disorders.
Carter, wearing red pants and a cream blouse, listened to the sentence standing, pressing her hands and lowering her eyes.
“With her actions she killed Conrad Roy,” the prosecutor told the court.
She interrupted his life to improve her own.
She did not accept responsibility,” she said.
“She did not show repentance.”
But Carter’s lawyer said it was “a tragic incident she deeply regrets.”
However, Judge Lawrence Monis said that, in his opinion, her "age, level of maturity or even mental illness had no noticeable influence on her actions."
The prosecutor read the statements of Roy’s mother, Lynn Roy, in which it was stated: “There has not been a day that I have not mourned the loss of my beloved son.
I want him to be proud of me and the way I do it – I try to support his sisters despite all the pain that will remain with us forever.”
Roy's sister Camden Roy said she was persecuted by the thought that she would never be able to attend his wedding or become the aunt of his children.
"To lose the person who has always been with me since I was born is a pain that will remain with me for the rest of my life," she said.
This case appears to be a legal precedent, as there is no law in Massachusetts that would provide responsibility for advising a person to commit suicide.
In 2014, when Roy was found dead in a car with symptoms of carbon poisoning, Carter was 17 years old.
The case caught the attention of the whole country when it became known that he was pushed to suicide by Carter's messages.
"You can hang yourself, jump from the roof, slay yourself with a knife, I don't know there are many ways," she wrote in several messages sent two weeks before his death, when he was resting with his family.
A few minutes before she committed suicide, she wrote, “You have to do this, Conrad” and “You just have to turn on the lighting and you will be free and happy.”
Judge Monis said Carter wanted to get attention through Roy's death, and forbade her from communicating with the press to prevent her from getting what she wanted.
The opinions of lawyers on this matter are divided.
One of the few who defended Carter was Amanda Knox, who was convicted in 2007 for murdering her British neighbor in Italy and acquitted two years later.
The 30-year-old Knox published her special opinion in the Los Angeles Times, which stated: "Michelle Carter deserves sympathy and help, not prison."
