Audi to modify up to 850,000 diesel cars
The day before the announcement by Audi, BMW said it would offer software upgrades to more than 350,000 vehicles.
The chairman of BMW said the company believes that “there are smarter roads than driving restrictions,” referring to European cities – including Munich, where BMW is located – that are considering banning or limiting the use of diesel cars.
Daimler said on Thursday it would modify three million Mercedes cars in Europe to reduce their diesel emissions.
None of the companies called their move a retreat.
European automakers have been actively promoting the use of diesel cars in Europe and the United States to facilitate compliance with CO2 emissions regulations.
But the nitrogen oxides emitted by diesel engines are considered carcinogenic and can cause asthma.
The cost for car manufacturers to install equipment that neutralizes diesel car exhausts is also increasing, andining a competitive car price is becoming difficult.
While German automakers are under close surveillance, Chancellor Angela Merkel’s government has also been accused of slandering influential automakers and ignoring signs of a problem.
The companies are trying not to repeat the mistake of Volkswagen, which hid the use of so-called "attack devices", which during the testing could counteract the amount of emitted harmful gases, so that it complies with the rules, and in normal driving conditions turned off.
In the United States, several Volkswagen executives have been convicted, the rest are under investigation on both sides of the Atlantic.
Last month, a former head of the thermodynamics department of the Audi engine development group was arrested in Germany.
Former manager Zakkeo Giovanni Pamio, an Italian, is therefore not protected from extradition and may face trial in the United States.
Earlier this year, Audi fell under a German criminal investigation involving Volkswagen after authorities accused Audi of installing a system to circumvent European emission rules and expanded an investigation that had previously focused on the United States.
The inclusion of Audi in the investigation could create serious problems for Volkswagen: the manufacturer of elite cars is the source of a disproportionately large share of the revenue of Volkswagen.
