Astronomers have discovered a planet where even iron can melt.
For the first time studying the properties of the stratosphere of a giant exoplanet called WASP-121b, astrophysicists were surprised by its temperature, which is able to evaporate iron and other metals.
The scientists noted that the water molecules are so heated by the light of the star that they emit infrared radiation.
The Hubble Telescope captured the shining of water molecules on this gas giant: this high temperature causes the water in the planet’s atmosphere to shine in the infrared range.
WASP-121b refers to the so-called "hot Jupiters" - gas giants, in size and mass comparable to the largest planet in the solar system, but located tens of times closer to the parent star.
Because of this, the year on the exoplanet lasts only 1.3 "Earth" days, and its gas shell is heated to almost 2,500 degrees Celsius.
