The murder of a journalist underlines that Mexico is becoming increasingly dangerous.
Officials of the Riodose newspaper usually meet on Wednesdays to discuss plans to cover recent violent crimes in the state of Sinaloa linked to organized crime, corrupt officials, or the ongoing drug dealer war.
But today, overwhelmed by their own tragedy, they met to talk about safety.
They were told to change their habits.
Two senior journalists discussed what seemed safer: taking children with them to an office that had already been bombed in 2009 or leaving them at home.
Security experts wrote three words on a board hanging in the room: enemies, neutral people, allies.
They asked journalists to name names for each column - no evidence is needed, suspicions and internal sensations will be enough.
These are drug dealers, politicians, businessmen, journalists who are suspected of being detained by the government or cartels, a whole list of criminals who make the work of disclosing chaos in Mexico dangerous.
Violence does not stop, and among the bodies that are multiplying in the country, there are more and more journalists: according to the Committee for the Protection of Journalists, at least 25 since President Enrique Pena Nieto took office in December 2012; 589 people are under federal protection after attacks and threats; and this year at least seven people have been killed in seven states.
Among the latter is their publisher and inspiration, the co-founder of Rio de Janeiro Javier Valdés Cardenas.
“The biggest mistake is living in Mexico and being a journalist,” Valdes wrote in one of his numerous books on drug-related violent crimes.
His absence feels very sharp, although his presence is everywhere – a large photograph of Valdes showing his middle finger, with the inscription “Justice” hanging on the façade of the Riodose building; two reporters years over 30, Aaron Ibarra and Miriam Ramirez, wearing T-shirts depicting his smile, face in glasses or his brand panama.
The seminar takes place less than two months after his death; journalists discuss their general trauma, their nightmares, insomnia, paranoia.
Although in 2010 the office of a special federal prosecutor was organized to investigate journalistic cases, so far, according to the Committee for the Protection of Journalists, only two cases have been investigated.
As with most of the thousands of drug trafficking and organized crime killings committed each year, the murderers of journalists are rarely brought to justice.
Riodose journalists insist that they will write about the violence in Sinaloa, although they are murdered by grief, though the surroundings are now much more dangerous.
Without information about the murderers, without justice from security talks at meetings, it is of little use, Ibarra says.
“It’s very stupid to waste time at this seminar,” he says.
“Until we know the reason, we suspect everyone.”
On the morning of May 15, Valdes left Rio de Janeiro’s office in the state capital of Culiacan.
He managed to drive only a couple of quarters before his red Toyota Corolla was stopped by two men; he was pulled out of the car and shot in it 12 times, probably because of the newspaper's name - which means "Twelfth River."
The gunman left his car and broke it nearby.
Valdes was 50 years old.
He has a wife and two adult children.
Rumors usually spread quickly across the Culiakan.
Almost everyone is silent about Valverde.
Since Guzman was arrested and extradited to the United States last January, Sinaloa has become one of the country’s bloodiest battlefields as rival factions struggle to fill the vacuum.
Let’s not talk about the fact that every day one or more people are killed on the streets of Sinaloa, or that the cemetery is filled with painted two-storey mausoleums of drug kings, which are more than the homes of many living people.
Forget for a moment that the state of "comfort" is simply when one of the cartels takes control of a seaside state with important ports and drug trafficking routes leading to the United States.
Despite this and the fact that Valdes was well aware of the dangers of his work, Ismail Bohorkes, a 60-year-old co-founder and director of Rio de Janeiro, is crushed by guilt for failing to protect his friend.
He believes that two mistakes helped the murder.
First, in February, an interview was published with Damaso Lopez, the leader of one of the rival factions of the cartel that is fighting with the sons of Guzman.
The publication could have angered the sons; people who were allegedly members of the gang bought all the copies of the publication as soon as they were delivered to the kiosks.
The second mistake was that he did not force Valdes to leave the country for his own safety after another newspaper that wrote about the same story was seized.
Valdes was a legend in Mexico and abroad, and his murder was seen as another milestone in the development of violence against journalists in Mexico.
He had been away from danger for so long, his friends and colleagues thought he would always be.
He was an experienced reporter at Noroeste and in 2003 together with five colleagues founded Riodose, selling his $50 shares.
In Sinaloa, "it was impossible to engage in journalism without touching the topic of drugs," Bohorkes said.
Over time, the newspaper earned the reputation of a bold and honest publication, sales and advertising revenues grew.
Journalists liked the fact that they could publish bold reports without fear of censorship, and readers were attracted to the fact that in this publication they could read about things that no one dared write about.
Eight years after its founding, Rio de Janeiro received the prestigious Marie-Murse-Cabo Prize for its reporter work in Latin America.
In the same year, Valdez won the International Press Freedom Award for his courage in investigating drug trafficking in Mexico, wherever it went.
He honestly admitted that he was scared.
“I want to live on,” he said at the CPJ award ceremony.
Drug trafficking in Sinaloa is "a way of life," he said last October in an interview with Rompeviente TV.
"You have to take on the tasks that lie on you as a journalist - either so, or you're just throwing a fool."
I don’t want to be asked, “What were you doing when there were so many deaths around... why didn’t you tell me what was going on?”
The employees of Rio de Janeiro are missing Valdes, a joke man who cried like a shipwrecker in the harbour, a friend who was generous at hugs and advice, a teacher who knew how to catch up with the living.
They rely on their order.
He should always wear his hat.
He had to go to El Guayabo, the bar opposite the office, and always sit there at the same table.
Now they ask: has his love for the once-established order destroyed him?
His death also caused them to question their calculations of how to do their job better and stay alive.
“They don’t like when you get caught up with their wives, their children, their legal business, and the underground airfields for drug trafficking.
“These things were beyond the line,” Bohorkes said.
The result, even in the best times, was a high level of self-censorship and a desire for self-preservation.
You have to trust your instincts.
Stay away from things that smell bad.
The problem, says Riodose editor Andres Villarreal, is that “the sense of smell can be deceived... and then what happened to Javier happens.”
The old rules, he and others say, are no longer valid in Sinaloa - as in Tamaulipas, Veracruz, Guerrero and other states, where there is a poisonous mixture of lucrative smuggling routes, weak government institutions and corrupt officials.
The landscape is constantly changing.
In the room where the employees of Rio de Janeiro gathered for security training, it suddenly turned out to be forbidden to bring cell phones: a few days before it became known that spyware, which is sold exclusively to governments, is used in Mexico to monitor journalists and public activists.
Outside, two police officers hide in the shade of a tree from a 104-degree heat (40 degrees Celsius).
They were commissioned by the state government to guard the Riodose office, which is located in a four-story building in the bourgeois quarter of Kuliakan.
Some of the journalists were half jokingly asking if these policemen were among the 50 percent of law enforcement officials that the governor himself said they could not be trusted.
A few months ago, journalists went to a mountainous area that is de facto controlled by drug gangs.
In the next issue, "Rio" counted on three main topics.
It is the murder in Sinaloa of the brother of the former boxing champion Julio Cezar Chavez.
They also exposed government spending concentrated in the governor’s hometown.
And there was a group kidnapping of people in one of the most expensive restaurants in Kuliakan, in a neighborhood from the prosecutor’s office.
It was not officially announced who was abducted or how it happened, so it was necessary to be careful when it came time to write about what everyone in the city knew: that it was a favorite restaurant of both drug dealers and authorities.
One of their journalists learned from open databases that the restaurant was registered in the name of a politician belonging to the ruling Institutional Revolutionary Party (PRI), which has dominated all levels of power for almost the last century.
Recently, several PRI governors were accused of corruption.
Villarreal asked journalists to write about previous incidents at the restaurant, including when Guzman's son "El Chapo" escaped the military.
A few months ago, readers would have been looking for the Valdez column with the most reliable information about the abduction.
"We would have already known what happened before," says the 46-year-old Villarreal, who is nicknamed "El Flacó" for his squalid body.
“Today, all channels of communication with our sources are broken.”
Valdez’s office is now being used as a warehouse for posters and stickers to protest the murders of journalists because employees have become what they never thought they would become: activists speaking on behalf of the press.
Journalist Miriam Ramirez took several posters and went on a demonstration next morning at the local prosecutor’s office dedicated to another journalist.
El Salvador Adame disappeared in the state of Michoacán in the west of the country three days after Valdez was killed.
They found the burned body, and the authorities said it was him, based on DNA tests.
Thro the country, journalists began to speak louder, organize protests and write "SOS Press" on the sidewalks and walls of houses.
That day, the director of Bohorkes was in Washington, D.C., trying to obtain international support in demanding justice in the Valdes case.
At a meeting with the governor of Sinaloa the day after the murder of Valdes, Ramirez accused the authorities of spying on journalists and ordering their murders for telling the truth.
After that, she asked not to give her any more tasks to cover the government’s activities, fearing that anger would damage her objectivity.
Valdes has repeatedly said that journalists in Mexico are "enveloped" by organized crime, its co-complices in the government, and the indifferent society.
In his latest book, “Drug Journalism,” he wrote that reporters are not just killed by drug gangs; they do so on the orders of politicians and security services in conspiracy with organized crime.
The Committee on the Protection of the Press Article 19 estimates that half of the attacks on journalists last year were committed by police and government officials.
“In Mexico, you’re dying because they want to silence you,” says Ramirez.
Of course, murders scare people.
Everyone remembers the death of blogger Maria Elizabeth Masías six years ago in the northern border state of Tamaulipas.
On her body a note was found, presumably written on behalf of the Zetas cartel: "I am here because of my articles."
The computer keyboard and headphones were lying next to her cut off head.
Some publications preferred to shut down, such as the El Norte newspaper in the northern border state of Chihuahua after its correspondent Miroslav Britch was murdered in March.
Others continue to hold on, like “El Manjana” from Nuevo Laredo after the assassination of its leader in 2004.
In 2010, Diario de Ciudad Juárez publicly addressed the drug cartels with an editorial article on the first page titled “What do you want from us?”
Some journalists have left their native states or the country in general.
This is a painful decision.
In exile, it is difficult to find work, and they still see danger on the streets.
And sometimes they are killed, as apparently happened to photographer Ruben Espinosa, who was killed in 2015 along with four women in an apartment in Mexico three months after escaping from Veracruz.
Those who stay and continue to work are balancing between risky decisions every day.
Ibarra - who once dreamed of being a poet - admits that he is scared to write about drug trafficking.
“Mexico is going to hell, and that’s why I became a journalist,” he says.
Last Friday, at midnight, when the last issue was ready to be printed, the Riodose publishers were sitting on the sidewalk next to the office and drinking beer when suddenly their phones were ringing at the same time.
A series of shootings between opposing gangs and security forces near the resort town of Masatlan left behind, according to confirmed data, 19 bodies.
The war continued to erupt, as promised in a series of messages from cartels discovered in the area.
Sitting on the sidewalk, they posted the news on the website of Rio de Janeiro via their mobile phone.
The next day I had to rewrite the first page.
In the vicinity there were siren raids - another shooting in the vicinity.
Bohorkes checked whether the police guarding them were ready for defense.
If they were scared, they did not show it.
Sitting under a huge portrait of the deceased founder of their newspaper, whose middle finger was displayed to view the whole of Sinaloa, the employees of Riodose continued his work.
“How can you think of closing down,” said Bohorkes, “if on the same day that Javier was murdered, a trainee asked me to send her out to do a report?”
Dinosaurs used camouflage to avoid enemies
At first glance, it looks like a statue, although it is horrifying.
The researchers said that the first found remains of an incredible creature the size of a rhino, discovered by a Canadian miner, were so well preserved that experts called it "Mona Lisa among dinosaurs."
It was so well preserved that they could even determine that the color of his peeling skin was red-brown – and say that he had, in some way, a “dark past.”
In a report published in the journal Modern Biology, it was described as “the best preserved Tireophorus in history of finds and one of the best dinosaur specimens in the world.”
This fossil is a newly discovered example of a nodosaurus that lived in the middle of the melting period, between 110 million and 112 million years ago.
His incredible good condition stunned researchers, who called him “truly remarkable.”
This herbivorous thyreophore is the best preserved fossil of this species in the history of discoveries, according to articles in the journal National Geographic.
It was found by Sean Fanck while he was working at the Sancor Millennium mine near Fort McMurray in northern Alberta, Canada, on March 21, 2011.
He stumbled upon something that seemed to be different from the surrounding breed, and decided to look closer.
The fossil he discovered was sent to the Royal Tyrrell Paleontological Museum.
For the next six years, work was carried out to find an animal inside the earth's crust weighing 2,500 feet (1100 kilograms).
Now that all this hard work is done, the finished result can be demonstrated.
“It’s only worth a little bit of sneezing, and you can almost believe he’s asleep,” said lead author Caleb Brown, a researcher at the Royal Tyrrell Paleontological Museum, where the creation is being demonstrated.
“It will enter the history of science as one of the most beautiful and best preserved dinosaurs – the Mona Lisa among dinosaurs.”
By examining his skin, the researchers found that this herbivorous, despite being covered with armor and resembling a walking tank, was apparently exposed to a significant danger from the carnivorous dinosaurs.
This powerful armor-covered dinosaur used red and white camouflage to hide from predators, and used a protective technique known as protective coloring, which is also used by many animals today.
This would allow him to fuse with the environment faster and avoid encounters with enemies, experts say, suggesting that he was hunted by larger dinosaurs.
This 110 million-year-old creature, belonging to the family of nodosaurs, was widely exposed in the press in May and is now on display at the Royal Tyrrell Paleontological Museum.
Scientists have already studied the animal and named it Borealopelta markmitchelli in honor of the museum laboratory assistant Mark Mitchell, one of the members of the group who spent more than 7,000 hours excavating it.
The surprising preservation of the specimen allowed Dr. Mitchell and an international team of scientists to document the pattern and shape of the scales and armor plates on his body.
They discovered protective coloring, a common method of protection in the animal kingdom, meaning that the top of the creature was darker than its lower side.
Although protective coloring is common, the discovery was a surprise, because the size of the Borealopelta dinosaur is much larger than the size of today's protective colored animals.
It can be assumed that this dinosaur was so actively hunted by carnivorous dinosaurs that evolution preferred to mask confrontation as a way of survival.
But most modern protective-colored animals, such as deer, zebras, or armored bearers, are significantly smaller in size and are more affordable prey, suggesting that the nodosaure had to fight seriously for survival.
“The serious threat from predators to a massive dinosaur covered with powerful armor shows how dangerous the predatory dinosaurs of the Mill era were,” Brown said.
Chemical analysis of the organic compounds in the dinosaur's scalp also suggests that his skin must have been red-brown.
Scientists continue to study the animal, looking for information about his life, including the preserved content of his digestive tract, to find out what he ate during his last meal.
They believe that when the dinosaur died, it fell into the river and was taken to the sea, where it sank and fell back down to the ocean floor.
At that time, Alberta was as warm as it is now in southern Florida, and the rivers and oceans were likely to spread much deeper into the land than they are now.
“This nodosaurus is truly remarkable because it is completely covered with preserved peeled skin, and at the same time fully preserved in three dimensions, preserving the original shape of the animal,” Brown said.
“As a result, the animal now looks almost the same as it looked at the time, in the Early Melting Period.
It is not necessary to resort to the imagination to recreate it, it is only necessary to squeeze a little, and you can almost believe that it is asleep.
The melting period is the era when giant teropods, flesh-eating dinosaurs standing on two legs, wandered the Earth.
Although the most remarkable of them, the Tyrannosaurus Rex, lived millions of years later than Borealopelta, a tyrannosaurus could have been hunted by one of its terrible ancestors.
These include the acrocantosaurus, a 38-foot-long monster (11.5 meters) weighing six tons.
Scientists, whose latest discoveries are published in the journal Modern Biology, believe that Borealopelta was taken to the sea after his death and mummified in clay.
