On average, these creatures reached about 18 feet (five meters) in length and weighed up to 3,000 pounds (1300 kilograms).
Their characteristic feature was two twenty-inch spikes coming out of their shoulders.
The researchers believe that this herbivorous thyreophore was hard on what is now Canada, until the spilled river took it to the open sea.
But the dinosaur's underwater burial preserved his armor with precision to the smallest detail.
The fossilized remains of this particular specimen are so well preserved that the remains of the skin still cover the bushy armor plates along the dinosaur skull.
As Michael Grechko wrote in an article for the National Geographic magazine, such a degree of security is “rare as winning a lottery”.
