How did one activist know the answer to the question “Who’s the streets?”
On August 9, 2014, Brittany Ferrell was shocked to the depths of her soul.
Just a day after arriving in New York as part of a tourist trip, a native of St. Louis was sitting on the bed in an apartment rented through Airbnb, browsing a Facebook tape on her phone.
She encountered the post of someone from high school.
“The police just killed an eighteen-year-old boy, and he’s still lying in the middle of the street.”
Noting that no one else in her tape had posted this information, confused, she closed Facebook and opened Twitter.
In her tape there were many user posts with the nick @TheePharoah.
A rapper from Great St. Louis in real-time tweeted the death of Michael Brown, an unarmed black eighteen-year-old teenager killed by a white police officer in Ferguson, Missouri.
He published a photograph of Brown’s lifeless body spread out in the middle of the street, where it will be for four hours.
“It’s wild,” Ferrell thought.
But death was nothing new to her and her circle.
She put off the phone and later in the evening returned to tweets that people were gathering for the Canfield Drive.
There were photos of a signal tape and screaming people and a man claiming he was Brown’s father, holding a poster with the words: “The Ferguson policeman just killed my unarmed son!”
She watched a live broadcast as a police officer stands in front of a group of protesters with a roaring dog.
In another video, another police officer, she said, picked up a rifle and shouted, “I’ll kill you all... animals!”
“It’s an unusual situation,” according to his own memories, Ferrel said.
"These are not murders like those we are used to and can be called typical.
At that moment I felt a cold.
I was angry and crying.”
She took her flight ticket and flew home the next day.
After landing at 11 p.m., she took her six-year-old daughter out of her father's house and decided that they would both go to Ferguson the next morning.
What happened to Ferrel and Ferguson over the next almost three years has been the theme of the new documentary “Who’s the Street?”, which will be released on August 11.
It’s a story of survival and protest, of love and loss, of strength and endurance from the point of view of people living in a community and filling streets demanding answers.
While Ferrell was travelling to Ferguson with her daughter dressed in a flower dress and a wreath of colour, they recalled the conversation, which had been held countless times before that morning, “about the experience of the Negroes and their position.”
She recalls saying, “Do you remember when I told you how black people fought for what they believed?
“We’re going to Ferguson now because a police officer killed an eighteen-year-old boy, and that was wrong.”
“I couldn’t help but take her,” Ferrell said later.
“What is happening today is the culmination of what happened before.
She should know about it, see it and be raised on it.
It must not only be well-known in activism and organization, but also understand the different levels of black experience and their position and what we must do to become free to free ourselves.
Even if I can provide her with an environment in which she personally will not face obvious racism, she is no different from any other black girl.
I feel like I would have done her a bad service if I had guarded her from it.”
When they arrived in Ferguson, they made their first stop at South Florisant Road, a site across the road from a police station that had become something like a tent camp, while activists were waiting for reports of the final innocence of officer Derren Wilson.
There, Ferrel and his daughter joined a local businessman who prepared lunch packs.
They gathered packages and helped distribute them to the protesters.
Gradually in consciousness, Ferrell took shape in a new type of activism.
“My activism completely changed after August 9,” she said, noting that as a student at the University of Missouri-St. Louis, she was president of the Association of Health Students, representatives of national minorities, and dealt with food justice and health inequalities among black communities.
I had no experience with the organizer.
It just came.”
A few weeks later, on an evening demonstration, Ferrell met Saba Folain, one of her co-directors.
Folain said she and her chief operator, Lucas Alvarado-Ferrero, “just wanted to document” the events.
Ferrell came to mind with the question, “Do you want to document, or are you trying to find a story to play on?”
This skepticism was driven by numerous people, often white people, who came into the community to benefit from its pain and persistence.
As Folaine explained in a recent interview, “We’ve heard that the voices of people who were born and raised in Ferguson don’t get into the spotlight, and we wanted to do it differently.”
By that time, Folain had already teamed up with her co-director Damon Davis, a local artist known for his activism on death penalty issues.
His participation aroused sympathy for the project in Ferrell and six other locals with whom the “Who’s the Street?” team had been in touch for years since Brown’s assassination.
“In this documentary, no one is speaking for us or with us, we are speaking for ourselves,” Davis said.
“It was most important to me how these people would be represented, because it was how I would be represented.”
And although the aim of the project was not to focus on the experience of Ferrell at all – in an effort to show that the movement “is not about the leader-saviour, but about how the community unites,” as Folain said – she proved to be the most open-minded of the film’s participants.
As a result, “Who’s the Street?” shows unexpectedly personal aspects of Ferrell’s life, such as how she fell in love and married her wife.
“I felt naked,” said Ferrell, laughing at how she first saw the finished product.
“But I understood that when you do this work and humanize black people, there must be some level of vulnerability.”
Furthermore, the Ferrel story once again discusses and emphasizes the role of a black gay woman in the broader context of the Black Life Matters movement.
