An artist creates portraits using Chelsea Manning’s DNA
In the center of the hall in the Friedman Gallery in New York City, people's faces hang from the ceiling on the wire - white, black and brown, all somewhat unfathomably similar to each other.
These 30 portraits were created by the artist Heather Dewey-Harborg from scratches from the cheeks and haircut sent to her by Chelsea Manning.
Manning sent scratches from Fort Leavenworth prison, where the former intelligence analyst serves 35 years in prison for the famous transmission of confidential diplomatic telegrams on the WikiLeaks website.
The new exhibition, which opened on August 2, is called "The Appearance of Similarity".
This is the result of a two-year correspondence between Dewey-Harborg, whose art combines technology, computer science and art, and Manning, a transgender woman and famous dissident to whom Barack Obama mitigated the sentence just three days before his presidency ended.
By analyzing the DNA obtained from Manning with a computer program and using it to create three-dimensional portraits of faces that people with such a genome could have, Dewey-Harborg created a profound, though difficult to perceive, manifesto dedicated not only to the plasticity of DNA data – the various ways of their interpretation and the inherent determinism of these interpretations – but also to the concept of identity.
Manning, who was born as Bradley Edward but has openly stated herself as a woman since her teenage age, was convicted in 2013 of 20 episodes, including six violations of the Spy Act, computer fraud and theft.
Her photographs in prison were inaccessible, so only one of her photographs was known: a grainy black-and-white selfie, on which Manning in a platinum-shade pearl, clearly feeling uncomfortable, is sitting behind the wheel of a car; with this photo she and became associated.
In 2015, Dewey-Harborg successfully completed her 2012 project "Visions of Strangers".
In it, the artist created portraits of unknown people using legal evidence such as cigarettes and chewing gum, extracting DNA from this garbage and creating images of how these people might look.
And then she received an email from Paper Magazine.
“They interviewed Chelsea Manning in jail and wanted some portrait to illustrate the article,” Dewey-Hagborg said at a preliminary presentation of the new exhibition.
At the time, Chelsea could not be visited and photographed, so they contacted her and asked if she wanted to get a portrait created from her DNA.
In this unusual way, the artist and her imprisoned muse became friends by correspondence and exchanged several letters over the course of two years.
They even wrote a comic book titled "Suppressed Images", illustrated by Shoili Kanungo, which depicted how in the future the president will soften Chelsea's punishment and she will be able to visit the exhibition personally.
The fact that Obama really decided to release Manning just days after the book came out was a pleasant surprise after seven tough years in a military prison in Kansas.
There’s something deep and powerful about the exhibition opening right now as Donald Trump declares war on people who disclose secret government information and invent new ways to incite Twitter hostility that he’s supposed to mitigate.
When Dewey-Harborg was asked about the coincidence of this all over time, she said that "nothing happens by chance."
In a statement written on the wall of the gallery, Manning’s huge signature at the bottom (with a heart instead of a point above “i” in her surname) calls for an end to “the automatic separation based on gender, race, sexual orientation and culture.”
On the opposite side is its mitochondrial DNA, a long hose of C, G, and A.
By incorporating 200 letters (or nucleotides, as the artist scientifically refinedly expresses), Dewey-Harborg hoped to show how we are all surprisingly similar, at least in their biological structure.
"I hope to explain to people that our genome does not determine what we are, how open genetic data is to interpret, and how subjective it is," Dewey-Harborg said; her 2007 video work, False Memories, is also displayed here.
“DNA data can tell us a lot of different stories, and 30 of those stories are here.”
The last part of the exhibition, which fits in the same room, is the aforementioned comic book.
On it, King Kong-style Manning appears over the building of the U.S. Correctional Cases with a speaker in his hand.
“If they kill your speech, they will win,” it says.
“So never be silent.”
“This is a direct quote from the letter she wrote to me,” says the artist who welcomes us from Philadelphia.
“I still have skin cramps when I’m talking about it.”
Manning hasn’t seen the exhibition personally yet – as it was provisionally depicted in the comics – but when she arrives, she’ll be welcomed by masks in the center of the room, her own genomic simulacres gathered together like crowds of protesters.
This was also done intentionally, like everything on the exhibition up to the height (5"2, Manning's height), on which genetic haplogroups were drawn with a pencil.
“I used to hang them on the walls, but now I wanted them to look like a crowd of people,” says Dewey-Harborg about the portraits.
“I wanted them to be like the mass movement that formed around Chelsea, as the movement that stood behind her liberation.”
