Startups that will help your company not to become the next Uber
Amy Errett wanted to assess the level of satisfaction among her e-commerce startup employees, but the surveys didn’t work.
The answers were often vague, useless, or worse, dishonest.
And even though she promised anonymity, some employees did not trust the process.
“He’s never been consistent and objective,” said Errett, who runs a 75-member, San Francisco-based e-commerce hair care company called Madison Reed.
Therefore, he appealed to third parties for help.
Now there is a new type of HR start-up that helps companies find out how their employees feel.
By developing and licensing software that measures employee involvement, they allow companies to conduct express surveys, contact specific teams and demographic groups, offer employees anonymity and hotlines for complaints, and in some cases allow whistleblowers to bypass top management and contact direct management.
“Now we have tools like Strava and Fitbit for health monitoring, and where is Fitbit for your company?” says Jim Barnett, co-founder and president of Redwood City’s Glint startup, whose analytics software is used by companies to measure employee engagement.
Errett said she has gained a greater understanding of what her employees think and feel over three years of using Glint.
In addition to the express surveys and questionnaires of certain teams, the product offers a heat map of the company and shows in a visual form which units have more complaints and which managers have a low approval rating, allowing it to understand why.
Companies are gradually realizing that they need to control the situation at work, otherwise they will become another “Uber” who was involved in the scandal when a former employee posted a blog post describing an aggressive situation in which those who expressed dissatisfaction were punished.
For startups like Glint, the desire to control the situation is an opportunity for a profitable business.
According to the Financial Technology Portal, the global governance, regulation and compliance industry could cost more than $118.7 billion by 2020.
Convercent, a start-up in Denver, Colorado that helps companies prevent and detect bad behavior, noted a slight increase in interest and activity earlier this year against the backdrop of Uber’s falling reputation.
Convercent has 600 customers, including Airbnb, Microsoft and Tesla.
Recently, Uber appeared among the customers.
Like Glint, Convercent allows companies to send customized staff opinion surveys, collect confidential real-time answers, and view heat maps of problem areas.
It also provides a hotline for anonymous text messages that allows employees to report bad behavior.
And if the top manager is affected, the complaints go directly to the management.
“The public opinion court has seized the authority of the inspectors,” said Patrick Quinlan, founder and president of Convercent.
If it turns out that a company treats employees badly or behaves unethically, even if the inspectors do not intervene, the company could face costly consequences in the form of customer boycotts, employee outflows, and lawsuits, Queen said.
Ruby Tuesday, a chain of restaurants with more than 25,000 employees across 500 establishments, has used Convercent for more than a year to make sure employees are aware of the rules and procedures and offer an easy way to contact the company’s headquarters.
Previously, if an employee wanted to report a problem, he or she had to look for the head office phone or email number, file an official complaint and hope that it will be taken seriously.
It was often a frightening and uncomfortable experience, said James Vitrano, head of the Ruby Tuesday legal department, who said there was no normal way to track employee complaints.
Now that the company uses Convercent, problems that were previously hidden from managers sitting in offices in other cities or states – such as discrimination, harassment and unfair pay – can be quickly detected and addressed.
“I can approach a holistic, comprehensive understanding of the situation of employees,” said Vitrano, who heads the Ruby Tuesday network’s risk management group.
“And we are protecting our shareholders from legal proceedings with employees.”
According to Queensland, companies began to take ethics, values and employee engagement more seriously in 2002 after Arthur Andersen’s accounting firm collapsed due to ethical violations as a result of the Enron Case.
But it was only when “social networks” gained mass spread that companies realized they couldn’t keep their dirty underwear from spreading the virus online.
“Before starting to use technology to control ethics, people used hope as a strategy,” he said.
Both Glint and Convercent offer their software as a service, charging companies regular fees for using their products.
It is a business model and an opportunity that has been approved by venture capital investors who have supported both startups.
In February, Convercent received $10 million in funding from companies such as Sapphire Ventures and Tola Capital, resulting in a total capital of $47 million.
Glint received $10 million in November from Bessemer Venture Partners, resulting in a total capital of $60 million.
These investments are unlikely to be surprising given the interrelated nature of companies, culture and venture capital.
A growing volume of research shows that today’s employees expect more from their jobs than they did before.
In highly competitive markets such as Silicon Valley, high wages and exciting projects are just the necessary minimum.
Employees want to feel that they are accepted and appreciated, and that they dedicate their time to the company with a positive mission.
“When people are happy to work in a company, feel that they’re being heard and that the work they’re doing is productive, they’re more willing to make such a company successful,” says Nina McQueen, vice president of global benefits and employee satisfaction at LinkedIn, which uses both Convercent and Glint.
Investors get income when the business of companies from their portfolio goes well; business of companies goes well when employees are dedicated and involved.
If third-party analytics tools promise to increase employee commitment and engagement, it’s no surprise that they find support.
According to culture experts at workplaces, it is important to have data on employee engagement.
But the data is useless until the company’s trustees take action.
In fact, if a company asks employees for feedback, it can create the impression that changes are coming.
And if changes don’t come quickly enough, or don’t come at all, frustration can develop, and employees will lose interest.
“If you’re going to ask for 4,000 proposals, you should be prepared to hold 4,000 conversations,” says Russell Ruth, president of consulting at management firm Kotter International, who has seen companies make the mistake of relying too much on data collection.
“Because if you don’t go to the end, the staff will guess, ‘Have you really heard me?
Do you care?
And if you don’t care, why don’t I care?”
According to Errett, Madison Reed, which now conducts monthly employee surveys, is able to take action on the same day that someone reports a problem using Glint.
And, after collecting feedback from employees dissatisfied with the speed of decision-making and the quality of communication, she was able to reorganize several teams within the company and introduce communication training to solve problems.
Ruby Tuesday is gaining new knowledge about its employees and hopes that in the long run this knowledge will help it to keep employees more efficiently in an industry known for its high flow of personnel.
“If you don’t try to create a culture of transparency, you’ll lose people,” Vitrano said.
If you lose people, you lose customers.
If you lose customers, you lose the company.
