Create a comic book: One Castle in English History
In the recent past, Scotty's tiny castle was filmed in the music video "Squeeze", and in the 70s and 80s served as a haven for Margaret Thatcher.
But 700 years from his cozy place in the Valley of the Bull River in Kent, he watched the tumultuous history around and now inspired Jamie Rhodes, a Yorkshire man with coarse hair and a tendency to historical documents, to a comic book.
“I think it’s so beautiful to look at the handwriting of a man who died 300 years ago,” he says with enthusiasm.
“You feel it so personally when you hold this letter in your hand.”
The Castle in England covers the period from the Middle Ages to the Everest and tells about the families who lived in Scottsdale; each story was illustrated by one of the young British artists – Isaac Lenkiewicz, Brian May Smith, William Exley, Becky Palmer and Isabelle Greenberg.
This is not Rhodes' first book based on archival data: in 2014 he wrote "Dead Man's Teeth and Other Stories" - a collection of British Library documents; this project unexpectedly touched him to the depths of his soul.
“I could be upset by just a fingerprint on the edge of a letter written in the 1700s by a double agent working for the Jacobites,” he says.
“This is his fingerprint.”
And letters always smell smoke, because in those times, fire was lit to illuminate.
And in 300 years, in the future, it seems to you that you are there too.
Oh, how I love the archives!”
For a person so overwhelmed by such a passion for old papers, getting support from the National Fund and the English Art Council and living in the castle for four months (“Honestly, I’m a bit overwhelmed there”) seems too good to be true.
Rhodes spent days studying the "new" Victorian castle, walking through the archives and examining numerous treasures of possessions and ancient things - for example, heads of hyens on the walls or bottles that have been lying in the roof for centuries.
He walked through the park and the ruins of the old castle, talking with foresters, gardeners and sometimes with artists working on illustrations for his book.
Then at night he “drinked whiskey and sat down to write.”
The history of the Scotty Castle is not much studied, because the National Fund only got full access to it in 2006, when its last heir, Elizabeth Hassy, died.
When Rhodes arrived ten years later, the staff had only begun to deal with the archive, which he describes as “what the aristocrats have been dropping down on the roof for centuries.”
Diaries, letters from the British Empire, maps showing who owned what: “You think land disputes are boring,” says Rhodes, “but two families fought for this breeze.
It is so, guys!”
In some stories of the collection, the castle becomes a starting point for broader exploration of English history: for example, in The Worker, the hero leaves the newly built castle to join the Peasant Revolution of 1381.
"There is information about the uprising that occurred in the castle in 1380 in a book called The Knights of Kent and Sussex," says Rhodes.
“The peasant uprising began in these places, and I thought the uprising was the right start.
Per they were connected?”
Other plots are closely connected with the history of the castle - for example, The Priest, which tells the story of a Jesuit priest whom the Darrell family hid for seven years during the English Reformation.
Or The Smugglers, about the 18th-century smuggler Arthur Darrell, who is believed to have orchestrated his own funerals by filling the tomb with stones (this was discovered a few years later when the tomb was excavated).
The Darrels were Rhodes’ favourite family of all who inhabited Scotty: “The gentlemen seemed to have been a complete fool, forever in debt and spent money on things they couldn’t afford.
Over generations, Darrell men have solved their debt problems by marrying wealthy older women – I imagine them as a company of nice guys who can take care of the heirs of great fortunes.”
After graduating from the castle, Rhodes is looking for other opportunities to gain a unique writing experience.
He lived for two weeks in a Finnish cave, where he wrote a graphic novel about Elyamiaki - a place where at the beginning of the 20th century there was a sanatorium, and then it was grown into a forest again.
But Scotty remains a special place for him.
“I was sad to leave,” he says.
"I felt like this: Fuck, I have to go back to real life again."
