Red meat, dairy products and chocolate can help ease IBS.
Red meat and chocolate are considered a nightmare for your digestive tract.
But recent research suggests the opposite: a diet rich in meat proteins and dairy products can help relieve symptoms in those suffering from inflammatory bowel disease.
This incurable disease, which affects approximately 1.3 million people in the U.S. and 300,000 in the UK, leads to colic and bloating, chronic or bloody diarrhea, weight loss, and extreme fatigue.
Usually, to ease symptoms, patients are advised to avoid meat and dairy products, but researchers from the University of Washington have found that the main amino acid protein tryptophan promotes the production of immune cells that increase intestinal tolerance.
Leading researcher Dr. Marco Colonna explained that immune cells in the intestines ensure that harmful microbes coming from food do not penetrate the body.
Cells capable of triggering the inflammatory process are balanced by cells that increase tolerance, protecting the body without damaging sensitive tissues.
If the balance is disturbed too much in the direction of inflammation, this can lead to inflammatory bowel diseases.
Experiments have shown that mice that have a specific bacterium in the intestine have cells that increase their tolerance.
And this bacterium needs tryptophan – one of the building blocks of the protein – to trigger the appearance of these cells.
Professor Colonna said: “We have established a link between one species of bacteria – Lactobacillus reuteri – which is part of a normal gut microbiome, and the development of a population of cells that increase tolerance.
The more tryptophan was in the diet of mice, the more these immune cells they had.”
He suggested that the same would work in humans: a combination of L. reuteri and a tryptophan-rich diet could contribute to a more tolerant and less prone to inflammation environment in the gut.
Postdoc Dr. Louise Cervantes-Barraganvas, studying a variety of immunosuppressive cells, found that one group of experimental mice had these cells, while another group, which belonged to the same line but was contained separately, did not have them.
She suggested that the difference could be caused by the intestinal microbiomes of mice—communities of bacteria, viruses, and fungi that normally live in the gastrointestinal tract.
The DNA of the intestinal cells of mice were sequenced, and six types of bacteria were found present in mice that had immune cells, but absent in mice that did not.
Mice raised in a sterile environment that did not have a good microbiome and did not develop this type of immune cells received L. reuteri, and immune cells appeared in them.
To understand how bacteria affect the immune system, the researchers grew L. reuteri in a liquid medium and then transferred small portions of fluid – without bacteria – to underdeveloped immune cells separated from mice.
Immune cells have become cells that increase tolerance.
When the active ingredient was separated from the liquid, it turned out to be a by-product of the processing of tryptophan, known as indol-3-lactic acid.
When the researchers doubled the amount of tryptophan in the food of mice, the number of these cells increased by about 50 percent, but when the level of tryptophan was reduced by half, the number of cells also decreased by twice.
Dr. Cervantes-Barragan explains that humans have the same tolerance-enhancing cells as mice, and most of us have L. reuteri in their gastrointestinal tract.
It is not known whether the by-products of tryptophan from L. reuteri contribute to the development of cells in humans in the same way as in mice, but in people suffering from inflammatory bowel diseases, defects in triptophan-related genes have been found.
She says, “Per we need to boost the development of these cells, because the inflammatory processes on the inner surface of the intestines depend on these cells.
High levels of tryptophan in the presence of L. reuteri may potentially lead to the expansion of their populations.”
According to Jose Mourinho, Manchester United hired “genius” in the person of Nemanja Matic
“Manchester United” hired a “genius” in the person of Nemanja Matic, says Jose Mourinho after the midfielder made his debut in the match against Sampdoria on Wednesday evening.
The player, purchased for £40 million from Chelsea, started with a 2-1 win in Dublin in United’s last pre-season match ahead of the UEFA Super Cup match against Real Madrid on Thursday and made an impression as a midfielder, while players like Paul Pogba and Andreas Pereira broke forward when they were pleased.
However, since Matic did not take part in Chelsea’s pre-season Asia tour, he was seriously lacking in preparation for the game, and he lasted only 45 minutes, which, according to Mourinho, requires refinement before the start of the Premier League season.
“He needs time, but his experience, his intellect, his genius in the way he thinks, he thinks in football,” Mourinho said.
“We’ll help him prepare sooner than too late.”
Just like Matic, his comrades-new players Victor Lindelof and Romelu Lukaku started the game at Aviva Stadium when Mourinho began forming his main team by the beginning of the next season.
The Independent newspaper this week that Mourinho wanted to hire three more players, but stressed that the club has already achieved fantastic results by hiring three of the four players he would like to hire first.
“I am grateful to the club for getting three out of four,” he added.
“I’d be even more pleased if they got me four out of four, but they’ve done a lot for me.”
Former leaders of Lithuanian Social Democrats urge them to remain in the ruling coalition
Former Chairmen of the Social Democratic Party of Lithuania, former Prime Ministers Algirdas Butkevičius and Gediminas Kirkilas, as well as the former Speaker of the Seimas from the Social Democrats Cheslovas Jurshenas appealed to the one-party with an appeal to remain in the ruling coalition.
As by the "Parliamentary newspaper", due to friction with partners - the Union of peasants and "greens" - the Social Democratic Party initiated a discussion whether to stay in the ruling coalition.
Three senior experienced comrades addressed the same party with an open letter, in which, in particular, it is said: "It is clear that the comrades in the party are disappointed with the results of the elections, but the coalition with the "peasants" has created for us, though not very easy, but still conditions for the further implementation of the goals of social justice, which are provided on our initiative in the program of the government, and for the preservation of the political domination of the left center over the right parties."
According to the former leaders of the party, in the discussion so far "the emotional expression of opinion without concrete arguments prevailed."
The authors of the letter fear that unconscious actions of their party could lead Lithuania to political, economic and social instability.
Invalid Anton Mamayev was fined
The Moscow city court mitigated the punishment of the wheelchair driver Anton Mamayev from four and a half years in prison to a fine of 200 thousand rubles.
Earlier, by the decision of the Timiryazevsky court, the convicted was released from the SIZO.
At the same time, the Moscow city court confirmed that the accused is a criminal, because he organized the robbery and the abduction of a motorcycle from a former fighter of the special forces.
The Moscow city court mitigated the punishment of Anton Mamayev to 200 thousand rubles. fine.
“Mamaev is the organizer of the robbery, which also forms the composition of the crime, and, accordingly, such a person should be brought to criminal responsibility,” said the press secretary of the Moscow city court, Ulyan Solopov.
In this case, the court has taken into account the state of health of Mamasev, the actual circumstances of the case, the absence of aggravating circumstances.
In addition, the court applied Article 64 of the Criminal Code of the Russian Federation, according to which it is possible to impose a sentence below the lower limit.
As for the assistant of Mamayev Vasily Serostanov, the court did not establish circumstances that would be the basis for changing the category of gravity of the perpetrated crime and changing the sentence.
Anton Mamayev himself said that he remained dissatisfied with the decision of the Moscow city court.
I am disappointed with the court’s decision.
The only legitimate solution would be an excuse, I intend to continue to fight for justice.
His lawyer Andrei Orlov did not exclude appeal of the verdict in the cassation instance of the Moscow city court and the Supreme Court.
"We will use all leverages up to the European Court of Human Rights," he told RIA Novosti.
The 28-year-old Moskvich Anton Mamayev, suffering from spinal muscle atrophy, became a figure in the criminal case in the fall of last year.
The disabled claimed to have bought a motorcycle from friends for 160 thousand rubles, then sold it.
However, the owners of the motorcycle, including a former fighter of the special forces, said that the disabled and his assistant Vasily Serostanov took away their property, threatening to use violence.
On June 30, the Timiryazevsky district court of Moscow sentenced Vasily Serostanov to three years in a colony, and Anton Mamayev - to four and a half years in prison with serving a sentence in a colony of general regime (according to Part 2 of Article 162 of the Criminal Code of the Russian Federation).
After the immobilized disabled was placed in SIZO, the Public Chamber, the Prosecutor General’s Office, the Human Rights Commissioner under President Tatyana Moskalkova joined the case.
As a result, in mid-July Anton Mamayev was released from the SIC by the decision of the same Timiryazevsky court.
The defense, in turn, appealed the decision of the first instance in the Moscow city court.
UNFCCC prepares environmental report to the President
The final “Action Forum” of the All-Russian People’s Front (ONF) in 2017 will be devoted to environmental issues, a source in the ONF told Izvestia and confirmed the head of the executive committee of the movement Alexei Anisimov.
According to him, according to the results of the forum, the "frontists" plan to prepare a report to the president on the problems of domestic ecology, as well as to propose a strategy for their solution.
Interlocutors of Izvestia in the ONF noted that the report to the head of state will contain "deep analysis" on the situation in all federal districts of the country.
According to "Izvestii", the final forum of the ONF will be held in the autumn.
The exact date of its holding has not yet been determined - as a rule, it is adjusted to the schedule of the president, who is the leader of the movement and traditionally is present at key events of the ONF.
The Front held several interregional environmental conferences, one in two federal districts - in Rostov-on-Don, Kaliningrad and Kirov.
The conference will be held in the capital of the Republic of Buryatia, Ulan Ude.
On the basis of the proposals that were made and will be made at these events, we will form systemic proposals for the solution of environmental problems, - told Izvestia an interlocutor in the ONF.
Olga Timofeeva, co-chair of the Central Headquarters of the State Duma’s Committee on Ecology and Environmental Protection, said that the frontmen will report to the head of state on the work carried out within the framework of the Year of Ecology in Russia.
The final environmental forum and the “Action Forum” of the ONF will most likely be combined.
Over the year, we have grown up with a powerful team of experts in the field of environmental problems, seen gaps in the legislation, stopped dozens of violations of the law.
All this will be included in the report that we prepare to the President as the leader of our movement.
In addition to this document, the "front workers" report on the work on priority projects of the ONF, - told "Izvestia" Olga Timofeeva.
According to her, the special representative of the head of state on environmental protection, ecology and transport Sergei Ivanov will be invited to the forum.
Earlier, he had already participated in the work of the ONF Media Forum, which took place in St. Petersburg in April.
In a few months, the Year of Ecology will go into history, and the most important thing to do today is to launch environmental mechanisms so that they work for many years.
So that these issues do not fall out of the agenda, - added Olga Timofeeva.
Head of the laboratory of regional policy of the Expert Institute of Social Studies (EISI) Andrei Kolyadin noted: raising environmental issues, the ONF acts in line with the presidential agenda.
Many things they as experts offered on various forums, and these initiatives received the support of the president, - said "Izvestia" Andrei Kolyadin.
He stressed that at present, the economic potential of the environmental agenda cannot be excluded, which can give regions an additional impetus for development.
In the future, with the help of the ONF, the regions will be able to lobby not only the solution of their environmental problems, but also the development of ecotourism.
The relevance of environmental themes was demonstrated by a “direct line” with Vladimir Putin in June.
In particular, the president was asked questions about the garbage landfill in Balashige (already closed) and about coal dust in the port of the city of Nakhodka (already developed a bill on the prohibition of the open transfer of coal in settlements, one of the authors - Olga Timofeeva).
Experts in the field of ecology believe that the legal basis for solving environmental problems in Russia as a whole has been created, the issue lies in further law enforcement practice, as well as in the position of civil society.
We need a clear implementation of the decisions made by the state, - says the head of the charity "Ecology for all" Leonid Bochin.
The head of the non-governmental organization "Greenpeace of Russia" Sergey Cyplenkov in a conversation with "Izvestia" stressed that a responsible approach of society and business is necessary to successfully solve environmental problems, and there are few legislative efforts.
As soon as society and business realize that solving environmental problems is a much more profitable step in a strategic perspective, the situation will change, - said Sergey Cyplenkov.
The expert stressed that it is necessary to reverse the trend that violation of environmental legislation is an economically beneficial solution for business.
British inventor implements a microchip to get into the house and car by shaking his hand
The British inventor became the first person in the country to be installed a microchip so that he could open the door of his home, enter the office and even start a car with a simple handshake.
Thirty-three-year-old Stephen Northam has embedded a tiny chip between his thumb and index finger and now through his firm BioTech offers this service to companies and individuals who want to simplify their lives through technology.
He teamed up with Dr. Jeff Watson, an anesthesiologist consultant at Royal in Winchester, to ensure that the injection procedure was carried out in accordance with medical standards.
The technology is similar to a microchip that is injected to cats and dogs, and the procedure takes only 30 seconds.
Northam also replaces locks in homes and cars with chip-compatible locks at a price of £300 per lock.
A married father of one child has already installed the technology in his home and in his car "BMW Z4", which starts when his hand lies on the steering wheel.
Requirements for the White House cost taxpayers thousands of dollars
According to military records provided to Time magazine, the White House’s decision last month to drive a naval helicopter to the Southern Grove for an event dedicated to U.S. industrial production cost taxpayers as much as $24,000.
The white-green Sikorsky VH-3D, known as the "Marine One", when the president is on board, became a central element of the July 17 White House event, which demonstrated American construction programs.
President Donald Trump, Vice President Mike Pence and senior White House officials examined technology products from all fifty states.
The Connecticut-made helicopter was displayed next to a Maine yacht, a Wisconsin fire car, and a Mississippi carloader.
According to records from the First Squadron of Marine Helicopters (HMX-1), the department responsible for controlling the helicopter, the White House Military Administration ordered the presence of the helicopter in a private order, or FRAGO, only 36 hours before the helicopter landed on the South Pond for an “unusual” event.
"I just wanted you to make sure you are aware because this is an unusual event widely covered in the press," the commander of the HMX-1 wrote in an email to his chief, the first deputy chief of aviation of the Marine Corps, on the eve of the event.
The letter indicated that the helicopter would arrive on the Southern Grove at about 7 a.m. on July 17 to participate in an event scheduled for 3 p.m. and would stay there until the lawn was released between 6 and 9 p.m. on the same day.
The letter adds that if the departure from the White House is delayed, a second crew will be required for the return flight in accordance with the working hours limits.
The first crew accompanied the helicopter during the event, and security personnel remained next to the aircraft while it was on the ground.
From the records obtained by Time magazine, it remains unclear whether a second crew was needed.
The Hatch Law prohibits federal officials from using state property for political purposes.
According to the records, HMX-1 clarified whether the event does not contradict this ruling.
“Among other things, we asked if this was a violation of Hatch’s law, and we were answered that not,” the commander wrote.
“You seem to have nowhere to go,” the deputy chief replied.
The “Made in America” event was declared by the White House as an official event, and the Hatch’s law did not apply to it.
But even official events have political notes.
During the event, the president made efforts to advance the health care reform that was being developed at the time in the Senate, and praised attempts to regulate government regulations.
The use of aircraft known as “Marine One” and “Air Force One” for political purposes is hardly a new phenomenon.
Presidents are ordered to use them for travel.
But asking for them solely for the sake of photography is unusual.
Trump was already the subject of discussion in February, when a presidential plane flew in the background during his first election rally in Melbourne, Florida, and his Twitter account was overwhelmed by messages complaining that his predecessor had used the presidential plane.
"The White House is delighted with the 'Made in America' show, which showcased products from 50 states made by American workers from American materials," White House spokeswoman Lindsey Walters said.
HMX-1 crews frequently perform training flights around the Washington agglomeration and on the South Pond to train transporting the President of the United States to the White House with an inch-to-inch accuracy.
When Trump was at the G20 summit in Germany in early July, HMX-1 had 58 training landings near the White House.
According to one of the officials, the flight performed for the "Made in America" event was counted to the crew as necessary training flights for the month.
Helicopters also flew 11 additional hours on the day as part of “non-presidential support tasks.”
According to the White House, taxpayers did not pay for any of the other exhibits presented at the event.
A spokesman for Sikorsky said the company did not participate in the organization of the demonstration of the helicopter on the Southern Grove.
HMX-1 does not account for the budget for presidential flights, and it is difficult to determine the exact amount spent on the event.
But according to the Defense Ministry’s hourly rates for the 2017 fiscal year, the Defense Ministry’s reimbursement rate for the VH-3D is $24,380 per flight hour.
The unit’s records recorded that the aircraft’s time in the air was 30 minutes in each direction from its airfield based at the Naval Infantry Aviation Base of Quantico in Virginia.
The White House claims that the actual cost of using the helicopter is much lower than that rate.
“Calculating the cost for taxpayers based on an approximate rate of reimbursement is completely wrong,” says Walter.
“These approximate rates include staff, service and many other irreversible costs that are included in annual allocations.”
According to a study conducted in 2015 by REND Corporation, the compensation rates do not include the cost of staff, but actually take into account the cost of fuel, maintenance and expenses specified in the contract.
At the time, former White House spokesman Sean Spicer spoke in defense of the use of the helicopter for the event.
“The idea is to demonstrate this week the things made in America,” Spicer said.
“And I know that Sikorsky and Connecticut are very proud of their contribution to national security, and that there are, I guess, hundreds, if not thousands of people whose jobs depend on it.
And I think, like most Americans, that we are all proud of this helicopter and other military equipment that so many Americans have worked tirelessly on.
Therefore, it is appropriate to pay attention to this.”
It was unclear whether Trump interacted with the helicopter while inspecting the South Pebble during the event, but he was sure to sit in the driver’s seat in a fire car.
Inside the White House, Trump addressed representatives of Sikorsky, joking with the press about his own fleet of company products.
“I know Sikorsky very well,” the president said, “I have three.”
Moscow to allocate grants for resuscitation departments of city hospitals
Each year, grants "Saving Lives" will be allocated to resuscitations and intensive care departments of the capital medical clinics.
The funds will be used to encourage doctors and nurses.
The mayor of Moscow Sergey Sobyanin visited the City Clinical Hospital named after Yudin.
During the examination of the clinic, he handed a letter of thanks to the physician-traumatologist-orthopedist Viktor Prozko, under whose supervision the most complex surgery was carried out to reconstruct the foot of the teenager.
Sergey Sobyanin also spoke about the decision to allocate grants annually to resuscitations and intensive care departments of urban clinics.
The funds will be used to encourage doctors and nurses.
According to the mayor of the capital, the clinical hospital named Yudin is one of the largest in Moscow.
In recent years, the clinic has received new modern equipment, allowing its doctors to perform unique operations.
The clinic was opened in 1961 on the basis of Kolomenskaya rural hospital.
At present, the departments of the medical institution are designed to receive more than a thousand patients.
In addition to the resuscitation and the hospital there are day rooms.
The staff of the hospital is 2800 people.
The total area occupied by the medical clinic is 23.7 hectares.
In February this year, the medical institution became a participant in the pilot project on the organization of short-term hospitals (SKP).
They are designed for conducting relatively small operations.
In the process of surgical interventions, advanced medical equipment is used, which allows to significantly reduce the time of rehabilitation of patients.
After the operation, they only spend a few hours in the hospital.
Only in the first half of this year in the clinical hospital named Judin was provided hospital care to 36 thousand patients.
The medical staff of the clinic performed 15,800 operations of varying degrees of complexity.
NBU announced the absence of buyers of the Ukrainian "daughter" of Sberbank
The National Bank of Ukraine (NBU) on the absence of applications for the purchase of the Ukrainian "daughter" of Sberbank.
This was on Friday, August 4, TASS with reference to the representative of the press service of the NBU.
NBU confirms that on August 3, 2017, a package of documents from the citizen of Belarus and Cyprus Viktor Prokopen for the agreement of the indirect (through Paritetbank) acquisition of 100 percent of shares of Sberbank was withdrawn.
"Documents from other potential investors for the purchase of shares of Sberbank in the NBU did not come in," the statement said.
On August 3, Belarusian businessman Viktor Prokopiya withdrew the application for the purchase of the subsidiary structure of Sberbank.
On July 28, it became known that the National Bank of Ukraine refused to Russian businessmen Said Guceriyev and Grigory Gusellnikov to acquire the Ukrainian "daughter" of Sberbank.
The regulator justified its decision by the fact that businessmen did not provide the necessary documents to verify their compliance with the requirements of the legislation of Ukraine.
Sberbank announced the sale of its Ukrainian "daughter" to the Norvik Banka consortium and a private Belarusian company in March this year.
The majority shareholder of the consortium was Said Guceriyev, the son of Russian businessman Mikhail Guceriyev.
Sanctions against the "daughters" of five Russian banks in Ukraine, among them Sberbank, were introduced in mid-March.
During the year, they are forbidden to withdraw capital from the country in favor of parent organizations.
