Democracy in Afghanistan depends on the role of women in politics, the UN said.
Elections can only be representative if all members of society, including women, participate, the head of the UN mission in Afghanistan said on Wednesday.
According to Nicholas Haysom, the current head of the UN assistance mission to Afghanistan, hundreds of women are running for provincial councils, three women are fighting for vice president, and more than 30 percent of newly registered voters are women.
“The role of women cannot be overestimated,” he said in a statement on Wednesday.
Elections can only be fully representative if women are fully involved and included in all stages of the electoral process.
Elections to provincial councils and presidential elections will be held in Afghanistan on April 5.
The Taliban threatens to disrupt the election process, which coincides with the transition of international forces from combat operations to the role of advisors.
At this year’s elections, power passes peacefully from one democratically elected government to another.
Heysom said that increasing the role of women would contribute to the success of democracy in Afghanistan.
According to the Independent Electoral Commission of Afghanistan, of the total number of 3.6 million registered voters, 1.2 million are women.
Prosecutor General approved the indictment in the case of Nikita Białych
The Prosecutor General’s Office of Russia has approved the indictment in a criminal case against former governor of the Kirov region Nikita Białych, accused of receiving a large bribe.
This was on Thursday, August 3, the ministry, reports RIA Novosti.
The material was submitted to the Presnensky district court of Moscow for consideration on the merits.
In Venice, heightened fines for tourists for inappropriate behavior
The Venetian authorities have tightened the fines for swimming in the canals from 50 euros to 500 euros.
Walking around the city in a swimsuit or with the naked torso will now be fined 200 euros.
100 euros will be required from those who arrange a picnic in a public place or ride a bicycle through pedestrian areas, TASS reports with reference to the Association of tour operators of Russia.
In addition, it is mentioned that the authorities provide for a fine for inscriptions on monuments 400 euros and for garbage 25 euros.
To inform tourists about the need to comply with the rules of conduct in Venice will be with the help of the special company "Enjoy, respect Venice" (#EnjoyRespectVenezia) in social networks, as well as through ads and posters on the website of the city council, on billboards and in places of the largest crowd of tourists.
The campaign will be conducted in 10 languages.
According to the tourism adviser of Venice, Paola Mar, information about the fines will be transmitted to the embassies of the native countries of the offenders, in order to warn their compatriots against such mistakes.
“The problem is that Venice is perceived as a beach,” she said.
In April, the administration of the Italian city announced plans to limit the tourist flow.
In Venice, there is already a successful limit on the number of tourists visiting the city center.
Instead of 100,000 people who wanted to watch the Festa del Redentore, only 60,000 were admitted to the venue.
In addition, a moratorium was imposed on the creation of new hotels and fast food restaurants in the historic part of Venice.
