National unions of unskilled, municipal and boiler workers (GMB) are concerned about capital investment at McVitie’s factory in Glasgow
The trade union demands guarantees from the managers of McVitie’s biscuit manufacturer in connection with its long-term commitment to production at the Glasgow plant.
The Scottish branch of GMB reports that the company has silently bypassed the question of future investments at the Tolcross facility.
The factory, which produces, among other products, Hobnobs cookies and Rich Tea, employs more than 500 people.
Pladis, the owner of McVitie’s, says it has invested more than £5 million in the facility over the past few years.
The company adds that in case of any changes in the work of the facility, employees and representatives of the trade union “will learn about them first.”
In a letter to the head of the facility owned by the company, GMB’s Scottish branch demanded McVitie’s response to concerns that funding will not be released for upgrading production lines.
Senior organizer Drew Duffy said: “Our union members are deeply concerned that we can’t get clarification from the facility’s chief executive on the business needs and investment plan for Tolcross’s future.”
Families have worked here for generations, and the concentration of workers is great in the local society and in Greater Glasgow; it is the most important pillar of decent work in the territory of high unemployment and social deprivation.
Thus, in terms of jobs, wages and prosperity, and against the backdrop of Brexit, rising livelihoods and chronic decline in production, East End Glasgow desperately needs a flourishing production at McVitie’s factory.
According to a spokeswoman for Pladis, “The head of the Tolcross facility just received a letter from the Scottish branch of GMB yesterday, and the company will respond immediately, as we appreciate our ongoing cooperation with employees and trade union representatives.”
Two months ago, we held a regular meeting with GMB staff and representatives in Tolkross, where we openly discussed a number of issues.
We talked to our employees that like all companies operating in the most competitive and volatile economic climate, we are constantly reviewing our actions – and this applies to all our facilities and areas of activity – to remain competitive.
“Over the past few years, we have invested more than £5 million in our Tolcross facility, especially in production lines and functional performance improvements.”
We are fully aware of the value of Tolkross as a production facility, and in case of any changes in the work at this facility, employees and trade union representatives will know about it first.”
Putin says Russia will not give instructions to Rosneft and Gazprom
Vladimir Putin said that the Kremlin and the Cabinet of Ministers should connect to the issue of gas supplies to the Eastern Petrochemical Company (VNHK), but no one will give instructions to Gazprom, as well as Rosneft.
