Did the PSG warn Barcelona about Neymar's transfer three years ago?
La Liga member may regret his interest in Marco Verrati
Paris Saint-Germain will not stop chasing Neymar after the club offered £189 million for his ransom, but did they warn Barcelona about a world record-breaking raid three years ago?
The sensational offer revived the summer transfer window when the League 1 club was ready to break the world record for the cost of the transfer, more than twice the previous mark associated with Paul Pogba’s return to Manchester United last season for £89 million.
When the transition is complete, Neymar will become the most expensive player in the world, as well as the highest-paid professional athlete in the world, as the PSG offers him a salary of more than £500,000 a week net.
It is known that Barcelona is furious at how the offer was made and how Neymar broke the contract, despite the fact that, as a source close to the management of the Catalan club insists, the club has always done everything possible for the player since his transfer from Santos in 2013.
But was the football world not warned of such a possibility three years ago by the PSG president?
When Manchester City expressed interest in hiring Blaise Mathieu in 2014, Nasser al-Helaifi issued a tough warning to any club that wanted to deceive one of PSG’s best players.
“I’m not worried because they know that if they touch one of our players, then we’re going to go against them, we’re going to make offers to their players,” he said.
“We respect all the clubs.
But if they try to recruit one of our players, they have consequences.”
It seems that Barcelona crossed this line when the Spanish club earlier this summer expressed interest in PSG midfielder Marco Verrati.
PSG has made it clear that it will not release the Italian player to the national team under any conditions, and now, probably, Barcelona is feeling the consequences of its offer in the form of the loss of one of its most valuable players, Neymar.
